<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH, WEST BANK -- Chief of the Palestinian Central
Statistics Department Hassan Abu Libda has disclosed that the
deficit in the current account of the Palestinian balance of
payments for 1996 stood at 805 million U.S. dollars for the West
Bank and Gaza (apart from Jerusalem).
</P>
<P>
This amount is almost equivalent to one fourth of its gross
national product in the same year.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Governor of the Syrian central bank Mohamed Bashar
Kobara Tuesday announced that a new monetary note of 1,000 Syrian
liras would be put into circulation as of April 1.
</P>
<P>
He said the objective is to improve the quality of bank notes
in circulation, and to replace the aging ones which were there for
many years. In addition, another bank note of 200 liras would be
introduced next month. The biggest note in circulation so far has
been the 500 lira notes.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) Airways has struck a
deal to buy 40 percent of the Sri Lanka Airways in a heated
competition with seven other international bids, Wednesday's "Al
Hayat" newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The UAE Airways will thus increase its foreign investments and
augment its financial resources, and will turn from a medium-sized
carrier into a world company capable of playing a leading role in
air transport in the region, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal El-Ganzouri has
announced that Arab and foreign investments in Egypt are expected
to exceed 20 billion Egyptian pounds (some 5.88 billion
U.S. dollars) this year, compared to 10.9 billion pounds (3.2
billion dollars) last year, local newspaper Alem El-Yom has
reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the national economic growth rate is expected to reach
7 percent this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
