<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Surges in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. construction spending
increased in February for the third consecutive month, with gains
in housing and government construction offsetting a dip in
commercial projects, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The 0.3 percent increase, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate
of 622 billion U.S. dollars, followed stronger gains of 0.7
percent in January and 0.8 percent in December, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Construction has been boosted in recent months by a drop in
long-term interest rates caused by Asian financial and economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The monthly growth was led by a 1.1 percent increase in
residential construction, to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
278.8 billion dollars. Single-family construction climbed up 1.9
percent and remodeling, 0.1 percent, but apartment building
declined 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Government construction rose 1 percent, the largest increase in
four months, to a rate of 140 billion dollars. Increases in
housing projects, highways and streets, military buildings,
offices and water systems offset drops in the construction of
schools, hospitals and sewer systems.
</P>
<P>
Commercial construction fell 2.6 percent in February, the
biggest drop since August 1995, to a rate of 158.9 billion
dollars. Private school and college construction rose, but
factory, office, hotel and shopping center spending all went down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
