<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain-German Joint MDI Base to Be Built in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Britain's Imperial Chemical
Industries Company will join hands with Germany's Basf AG to build
a chemical base in Shanghai to produce di-phenylmethane
di-isocyanate (MDI), a key element for polyurethane.
</P>
<P>
The base will cost 25 billion yuan for the first phase of
construction work and will be built up within three years. It is
expected to produce 160,000 tons of MDI a year.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be the third largest of its kind worldwide,
after the other two in the US and Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
China's demand for polyurethane rose to 500,000 tons in
1997 from 100,000 tons in 1980. China is expected to become a
center in Asia to produce items made of polyurethane.
</P>
<P>
The base is expected to help China save 200 million US dollars
in foreign exchange which was used for exporting polyurethane
before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
