<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Ministerial Meeting Ends in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The energy ministers from Germany,
Italy, United Kingdom, Canada, the U.S., France and Japan wound up
their one-day meeting here with a communique issued on the global
energy problems in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the Ministerial Meeting focused on problems
related to the prospects for the global energy markets,
development of competitive energy environment, energy
transportation and transit, energy investments and the energy
impact of the environment, according to the press release.
</P>
<P>
The communique noted in particular that ensuring reliable,
economic, safe, and environmentally sound energy supplies is one
of the underpinnings of sustainable development for their
countries and for humanity.
</P>
<P>
The signitories of the communique reaffirmed their commitment
to broaden international cooperation and exchanges of information
and experience in tackling global energy problems for the sake of
attaining this goal.
</P>
<P>
They believe that open and competitive energy markets offer the
best way to provide secure, reliable and affordable energy to
consumers, and stated that potential investors will take decisions
on the basis of a thorough analysis of political, juridical and
financial risks.
</P>
<P>
The ministers emphasized that non discriminatory access to
secured pipelines greatly contributes to development of regions
rich in energy resources.
</P>
<P>
The meeting reaffirmed the commitments of industrialized
countries to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 5.2 percent below
1990 levels in the five year period from 2008 to 2012 (Kyoto
Protocol).
</P>
<P>
The initiative about the G8 Energy Ministerial Meeting was
taken by the Russian President Boris Yeltsin in June 1997 and
supported by the Denver G8 Summit in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was viewed as an important stage in preparations
for a G-8 summit, due to be held in Birmingham (Britain) in May
1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
