<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo (K) Becomes Major Market for Zambian Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic Republic of Congo
has become a major market for Zambian goods, a Zambian minister
said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Commerce, Trade and Industry Minister Enock Kavindele said the
present value of non-traditional exports to Congo now amount to
40 million U.S. Dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
By exploring more trade opportunities in Congo, the value of
the non-traditional exports will increase to 100 million Dollars
in the next two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the ministry is in the process of appointing
a trade commissioner to be based in Lubumbashi, a border city
inside Congo.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is also exploring business opportunities in Namibia and
the United States, while goods such as beef have generated a lot
of interest on the South African market, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Zambia will sign a trade agreement with the
Southern African Customs Union next week to enable Zambian goods
to have an easy access to the southern African market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
