<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Hikes Aircraft Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government
Wednesday approved price increases of fuels used by aircraft by
between 16 and 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
Transport and energy minister Enos Chikowore said in a
statement that the prices of the fuels would be adjusted on a
monthly basis while an announcement on the prices of petrol,
diesel and illuminating paraffin would be made in due course.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the recent depreciation of the Zimbabwean dollar
against the U.S. dollar," he said, "the level of our fuel prices
cannot be sustained. The effect of the low prices is that traffic
is now coming from other countries to fuel in Zimbabwe,."
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's fuel prices are the lowest in southern Africa and
drivers of heavy vehicles travelling in the region are reported
to be coming here for fuelling because of the cheap prices.
</P>
<P>
However, the government is understood to be hesitant to
increase the prices of petrol and diesel in fear of triggering
protests by consumers since such increases would have ripple
effects on the prices of other goods.
</P>
<P>
The government's delay in adjusting the prices of petrol and
diesel is causing the state-run oil procurement agency, the
national oil company of Zimbabwe, to lose millions of dollars
every week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Asia-Europe Summit Poses Challenges (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Asian leaders will meet their
European counterparts in London on April 2-4 for their second
summit in great expectations of winning European support to
address the economic woes confronting some Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
But will the Asem summit live up to the expectations of Asian
leaders? There have been signs that the summit will pose
challenges to East Asian leaders who face a tough task to prod
Europeans into offering more aid to help shore up their battered
economies.
</P>
<P>
The summit is expected to focus on the currency crisis
besetting a number of Asian nations, while setting aside human
rights and other thorny political issues. Fifteen European Union
member states and 10 Asian countries will be represented.
</P>
<P>
The second Asem summit "is quite timely in the sense that we
are now facing this financial crisis," said Apinan Pavanarit,
director-general of the European Department of Thailand's Ministry
of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, where the currency crash first started, will explain
to European leaders what steps have been taken to restore
confidence. It will also ask European countries to roll over and
restructure corporate debts and provide export credits.
</P>
<P>
Other Asian nations will likely make similar requests.
</P>
<P>
East Asian countries have been unhappy about the slow response
by Europe to help out with Asia's crisis. The EU extended 1.5
billion U.S. dollars in export credit loans to Indonesia, Thailand
and South Korea in 1997 but have refrained from making greater
contributions ever since.
</P>
<P>
Europe is perceived by certain Asian countries to even have
lagged behind the United States and Japan in coming to the
region's rescue. Asian countries have complained that the United
States and Japan have not done enough to help them out.
</P>
<P>
"We shouldn't be friends just in times of prosperity, we should
be friends in times of need as well," said Apinan.
</P>
<P>
He said Europe was interested in Asia's problems because it had
a vested interest. European banks have loan exposure of 350
billion U.S. dollars in Asia greater than the U.S. and Japanese
bank exposure combined.
</P>
<P>
European diplomats also stress the continent's stakes in East
Asia, where EU exports totaled 123 billion U.S. dollars in 1996,
outstripping EU exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Asian officials were quick to note that despite the financial
crisis, a lot of progress had been made in the improvement of the
economic infrastructure and monetary system in the Asian countries
concerned, as well as in the improvement of links between the two
continents.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that given these conditions there remain great
potentials for Asia-Europe cooperation and therefore the EU should
play a greater role in helping Asian countries tide over the
present economic hardships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Asia-Europe Summit Poses Challenges (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In an apparent bid to show EU's commitment to the currency
crisis, host Britain has proposed setting up an Asia-Europe trust
fund to provide assistance to Asian countries, primarily in giving
technical advice to Asian countries on banking and other financial
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
European officials said Europe wants closer ties with Asia
which is expected to become a major market in the next century.
Two-way trade between Asia and Europe at present is around 15.8
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But Asian countries expect more and want the upcoming summit to
rectify the slow response by Europe towards the economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, on its part, has requested that a separate statement
be made on Asia's economic crisis, which would show Europe's
commitment to helping solve the problems.
</P>
<P>
But so far hopes for the statement looked uncertain, with
Britain neither agreeing to nor rejecting the idea.
</P>
<P>
"It's up to the leaders," Paul Sizeland, British Charge d'
affairs in Bangkok, told reporters earlier this week when asked
about the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Asem normally issues only a statement from the chairman at
the end of the summit. Having a separate statement on the
financial crisis would underline the importance of the issue.
</P>
<P>
Sizeland said the European side would push for a discussion on
child welfare, on building links between young Asians and
Europeans and on joint efforts to increase trade and investment,
protect the environment  Europeans also have requests for Asians.
Prior to the summit, EU officials required Asian countries to meet
certain conditions for obtaining more aid from outside, such as
fully opening the doors of their financial, insurance, agriculture
and other markets to foreign competition.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's prime minister Chuan Leekpai, in apparent reference
to the request, said recently that "we are not fully ready for
full globalization and liberalization and therefore we have to
take measures to protect our people from its (the globalization's)
full impact."
</P>
<P>
He said exceptions needed to be made for uneven economic and
social development in a world where some countries can send a man
"to walk on the moon, while in developing countries the people do
not yet have shoes."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tobacco Price Remains Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean flue-cured tobacco
marketing season entered its second day Wednesday with a total
sales of 694,959 kilograms at an average price of 1.25 U.S.
dollars per kg, the Zimbabwe News Agency Reported.
</P>
<P>
Generally, prices were way off last year's for the first days
which were pegged at around 2.08 u.s. dollars per kg resulting in
a relatively high rejection rate.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean tobacco sales market is one of the world's
largest tobacco sales markets. Tobacco is the country's biggest
foreign currency earner.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe News Agency quoted an official of the Zimbabwe
Tobacco Association as saying, "due to low prices there was a
high rate of rejection at the sales floors at an average 58.72
percent."
</P>
<P>
As expected this time of the year, the market was dominated by
primings. The situation was expected to be better later in the
season as more high quality tobacco would be brought forward by
farmers as prices firmed.
</P>
<P>
A total of about 210 million kgs was expected to be sold this
year earning the country about 540 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
