<HEADLINE> Kocharian Wins Armenian Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Robert Kocharian, who has won 59.3
percent of the votes already counted, has apparently been elected
Armenia's president.
</P>
<P>
About 99.4 percent of all ballots have been counted.
</P>
<P>
Kocharian's challenger, former Soviet-era Communist leader
Karen Demirchian, got 40.7 percent of the votes already counted.
</P>
<P>
The Central Electoral Commission has confirmed this result of
the second run-off voting, according to reports reaching here from
Yerevan, the capital city of Armenia.
</P>
<P>
According to the constitution, the nominee who gets more than
half of the votes in the second round of voting will be the president.
</P>
<P>
About 68 percent of the electorate participated in the polls,
the commission added.
</P>
<P>
Kocharian, 43, began his political life from 1980 and won his
war hero reputation during a six-year secession conflict in
Nagorno-Karabakh, the Armenian-populated enclave of Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
He served as the premier and acting president of the nation
before running for presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
