<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Warns Against Cholera Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Angola's Deputy Health Minister
Teresa Cohen warned Wednesday that 100,000 Angolans will be
infected with cholera if no measures are taken to improve the
country's general health condition and expand tap water supply
around the country.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks at the launching ceremony of a
government-sponsored anti-cholera campaign.
</P>
<P>
The recent heavy rainfalls around the country have given rise
to the eruption of cholera, she said, adding that her ministry
will take up a series of measures, including ensuring the quality
of tap water, eliminate possible infection sources and
distributing water disinfectants to residents, to reduce cholera
victims.
</P>
<P>
According to Cohen, a total of 114,701 Angolans were infected
with cholera last year, among them 751 died. Of the country's 18
provinces, Benguela Province in central Angola, Huila Province in
the south and Bie Province in the central highland were the
seriously hit, with the death tolls at 460, 137 and 352
respectively.
</P>
<P>
So far, she noted, only 46 to 50 percent of those receiving
injections could exempt from infection.
</P>
<P>
Cohen disclosed that her ministry will meet on the coming
Friday with some non-governmental organizations and
representatives from foreign embassies in Angola on possible
assistance in case of a sudden breakout of the disease in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
