<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Launches Financial System Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan Wednesday kicked off a major
financial overhaul designed to build a better banking system by
the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
As part of the long-awaited program, restrictions on foreign
currency trading will be lifted beginning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This could mean that instead of going to banks, Japanese could
soon be able to change their yen for foreign currencies at places
including supermarkets, department stores and airports.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese version of "Big Bang," nicknamed after similar
British financial reforms in the 1980s, is the core of Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's six ambitious reform programs,
which include administrative, economic structural, social welfare,
fiscal structural and educational reforms.
</P>
<P>
The "Big Bang" program will also liberalize brokerage
commissions on stock trades worth more than 50 million yen (about
378,000 U.S. dollars) and enact a law requiring weak financial
institutions to improve their management.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of these reforms, Japanese financial institutions had
already been teaming up with foreign institutions and been cutting
commissions on stock and foreign exchange transactions.
</P>
<P>
Upon the imminent passage of the fiscal 1998 budget by the Diet
(parliament), lawmakers will begin to discuss the second stage of
the "Big Bang" reform, which will include the abolition of
barriers between banks, brokerages and insurers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7.5 Million Indonesians Risk Food Shortage: UNDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Some 7.5 million Indonesians risk
experiencing food shortage until early 1999 because of the drought
and financial crisis in the country.
</P>
<P>
That is among the results found by a UNITED NATION DEVELOPMENT
PROGRAM (UNDP)-sponsored mission to Indonesia, according to a
press release issued here Wednesday by UNDP.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member mission, consisting of international experts from
the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the World Food
Program (WFP) as well as Indonesian consultants, assessed crop and
food supply in Indonesia for the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
The team found that the rice harvest in the next coming months
is expected to be below normal because of delayed and irregular
rainfall, reduced use of fertilizer and use of low quality seeds,
leading to possible record rice import requirements in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The experts warned that 1.5 million families or 7.5 million
people living in 15 provinces risk experiencing food shortage
until early 1999 if there is a renewed drought later this year.
</P>
<P>
However, the team found that production of most secondary crops
such as maize, soybean, cassava, sweet potato and groundnuts is
expected to increase, providing some food security cushion.
</P>
<P>
"We certainly could not call this situation a famine," said
mission leader Uwe Kracht, adding that many pockets of the
population are however facing acute food supply inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
"We are concerned over the food security situation of the
poorest in the country and hope to help them through emergency and
food assistance for a limited period of time," said UNDP Resident
Representative Ravi Rajan, who is also U.N. Resident Coordinator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
