<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Tobacco Production to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Due to the adverse effects
of the rains caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon, Tanzania's
tobacco production is expected to drop to 20 million kilograms
this season from 42 million kilograms harvested during last
season.
</P>
<P>
The decrease in production is likely to cause a loss of about
30 million US Dollars, The Guardian Wednesday quoted Michael
Filakos, chairman of the Tanzania Tobacco Council, as saying.
</P>
<P>
This year, Tanzania is expected to produce only about 35
million kilograms of tobacco leaves, as the excessive rains have
hindered the growth of tobacco and washed away a lot of
fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
Most farmers will harvest below their expectations and the
cost of production will be high, the official said.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, one tobacco harvest per year normally takes place
from mid January to April.
</P>
<P>
The main harvest months are February and March. Tobacco
planting is normally from mid-November to mid-March. The number
of people in the industry, including farmers and process workers,
is approximately 440,000.
</P>
<P>
Tobacco is Tanzania's sixth foreign exchange earner after
coffee, cotton, cashew nuts, tea and sisal.
</P>
<P>
The tobacco market in the country is undergoing a rapid
expansion after the privatization of Tanzania Cigarette Company
and the liberalization of the tobacco industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
