<HEADLINE> Syrian, Lebanese Leaders Discuss Israeli Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
held talks Wednesday with visiting Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri, who arrived here Tuesday evening from Saudi capital Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The content of the talks was not revealed, but was believed to
focus on an Israeli proposal on conditional withdrawal from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his talks with al-Assad, Hariri had had a second round
of talks with Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and other
senior officials on the matter and the latest efforts to rescue
the collapsing peace process due to Israel's hardline policies on
peace-making with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel proposed that it pull out of south Lebanon if adequate
security arrangements can be worked out with Lebanese government.
This offer has been rejected as a deception by Beirut, which
insisted that the U.N. resolution 425 calls for unconditional and
immediate Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Syria, a major power broker in the Middle East peace process,
favors a linkage between a solution on the Israeli-Lebanese track
and Israel's return of Golan Heights, captured from Syria in the
1967 war.
</P>
<P>
After Hariri arrived here Tuesday evening, he went straight to
talks with Khaddam, and later with Syrian Speaker of the People's
Council Abdel Kader Kaddura, Prime Minister Mahmoud Zouebi and
Foreign Minister Farouq al-Sharaa.
</P>
<P>
After the meetings, Hariri told reporters that Lebanon would
not make any security commitments to Israel, and that the
U.N. resolution 425 had to be implemented unconditionally and
without negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He hoped the ongoing intensive Arab contacts would result in an
action formula based on strong solidarity that would be capable of
confronting the new developments, changes and grave dangers
resulting from Israel's "deceitful proposal."
</P>
<P>
In Riyadh, Hariri had a series of meetings with Saudi King
Fahd, Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz and other top officials
in charge of regional affairs and inter-Arab relations.
</P>
<P>
He also met with foreign ministers of Egypt, Syria and Saudi
Arabia who were there to discuss the convocation of an Arab
mini-summit in a bid to reinforce the Lebanese stance on
unconditional Israeli troop withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
