<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OCHA Says Drought-Stricken Guyana Needs water, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 1 (xinhua) -- The United Nations Office
for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) said on
Wednesday that drought-stricken Guyana urgently needs potable water
and relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
In its latest situation report on Guyana, OCHA said that the
prolonged drought attributable to the El Nino weather phenomenon
continues to cause widespread deprivation and loss throughout the
country.
</P>
<P>
OCHA said acute problems facing the population were lack of
drinking water and shortage of food as sea water moved up stream
into areas of cultivation.
</P>
<P>
According to OCHA, in one region, an entire population of more
than 14,000 made up of mainly indigenous communities was facing
the threat of starvation and destitution.
</P>
<P>
In addition to crop losses in the rice and sugar sectors,
losses of livestock had also been reported, said OCHA.
</P>
<P>
OCHA said Guyana urgently needed equipment including hand,
submersible and mobile pumps for drilling a well and pumping
water.
</P>
<P>
The office said the families of the most affected rice and
sugar farmers needed financial assistance over a period of six
months. It also said the farmers would need paddy seeds for the
next cropping season.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Called on to Buy More from Developing Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Several member states have
called on the United Nations to award more procurement contracts
for peace-keeping purposes to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
During the on-going debate of the Special Committee on
Peacekeeping Operations, the Indonesian representative said while
financial obligations for operations were borne by the general
membership, the majority of procurements were being carried out in
a limited number of countries.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, Syria and Iran also emphasized the need to address
the current heavy buying from developed nations. The
representatives took the floor on Tuesday, according to a U.N.
press release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On the mandate of the peace-keeping operations, Cuba's
representative said peace-keeping operations could not be
considered as a substitute for peaceful resolution of conflicts,
but rather as a measure of last resort, requiring specific clear
mandates and reasonable chances for success.
</P>
<P>
On the Denmark-led Multinational U.N. Stand-by Forces High
Readiness Brigade (SHIRBRIG), some countries saw it as duplication
of the existing U.N. stand-by arrangements system.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia's representative said rather than promoting SHIRBRIG,
it would be more meaningful and effective for the U.N. to focus
on improving the existing system.
</P>
<P>
The representative of Kyrgyzstan said that among the
peace-keeping issues of concern to delegations were also the delay
in peace-keeping reimbursements to troop-contributing countries
and low geographical representation of civilian police officers at
higher levels.
</P>
<P>
The debate, which started on Monday, focuses on
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's five-part report including the
enhancement of U.N. capacity in peace-keeping operations and
cooperation with regional arrangements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
