<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sino-EU Ties Have Broad Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- A China-European Union summit,
scheduled on April 2-3 on the sidelines of the second
Asia-Europe Meeting, is regarded as a landmark opportunity for
further developing relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
China's new premier, Zhu Rongji, is to attend the China-EU
summit, the first since China and the 15-member European Union
established a formal diplomatic relationship in May 1975.
</P>
<P>
For the past 22 years, relations between the two sides have
maintained a positive general trend of moving forward, after
taking some windings and turns. Especially in the 1990s, the
relations entered a phase of development, with increase exchanges
of high level visits and closer cooperation in the fields of
politics, economy, science and education.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the then Chinese Premier Li Peng and Vice-
Premier Li Lanqing made separate visits to western European
countries. In return, some senior officials from the EU and its
member states toured China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders believe that the EU and China are both an
important force to safeguard peace and promote development in the
world. To develop an all-round relationship of cooperation which
is mutually beneficial with the EU and its members is an important
aspect of China foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, has stressed
the importance of both having a political dialogue and
strengthening the economic and trade ties with China in its China
policy documents respectively issued in July 1995 and November
1996.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday last week, the commission approved a policy
document on establishing an all-round partnership with China. It
called for strengthened political dialogue with China and an
annual summit meeting between the commission and China. If it is
adopted by the governments of EU member countries, the political
relationship between China and the EU will enter another new
period of development.
</P>
<P>
"China's growing economic and political self-confidence is an
overwhelmingly positive development. It should serve as an
incentive for the EU to engage the country more fully," said Sir
Leon Brittan, European Commissioner responsible for relations with
China.
</P>
<P>
Britain, the current EU president, welcomed the document,
saying it reflected "the growing breadth and importance of the
EU-China relationship" and Britain would ensure that EU ministers
gave it "serious and rapid consideration."
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the EU has revised its China policy in order
to fit in with its new global strategy and to enhance its political
and economic leverage in this increasingly multi-polar world.
</P>
<P>
The commission noted that the emerging leadership role of China
during the Asian financial crisis underlined the need for the EU
to further develop its political, economic and trade relations
with China.
</P>
<P>
China is a fast developing economy with a huge market potential
while the EU has advanced technology and investment funds. The
total volume of trade between China and the EU in 1997 reached 43
billion U.S. dollars, three times that in 1990. The EU so far has
had more than 8,000 investment projects in China, worth a total of
11.5 billion dollars. China and the EU are the fourth largest
trading partners of each other. The fast growing economic and
trade ties have laid a solid foundation for the development of
all-round relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
However, it is natural for China and the EU to have differing
views on some issues due to the differences in their social
systems, culture and ideology. But there is no conflict in basic
interests between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided in February not to sponsor a resolution against
China at this year's United Nations Human Rights Commission in
Geneva. The EU said in its document that it favored dialogue over
confrontation with China on the issue of human rights. It has
become the consensus of China and the EU members that in
developing relations, they should take an approach of expanding
common ground while putting aside differences.
</P>
<P>
Both Chinese and EU leaders are now working toward the
establishment of a cross-century China-EU relationship.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that such a relationship will surge forward as
long as the two sides observe the principles of mutual respect,
mutual benefit, consultation on the basis of equality and seeking
common ground while reserving differences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
