<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Prepare for Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Member states of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) were urged Wednesday to develop
skilled manpower if they are to enter the 21st century in a position
to compete favorably with industrialized countries, reported the
Zambia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the COMESA's committee on industry held in Lusaka,
Erastus Mwencha, Acting COMESA secretary-general, said that the
experiences of the 1980s and 1990s show that the the comparative
advantage previously offered by inherited natural resources will not
be of much benefit in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Low wage labor too will not present a guarantee on competitive
advantages, said the COMESA official, stressing that the nature of
competition in the 21st century will require innovation and ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
COMESA countries therefore, he said, will be required to find
an appropriate mix of lower and higher order production functions
which are supremely competitive.
</P>
<P>
He noted that COMESA members, however, can achieve growth with
equity if industrialization and promotion of agro industries become an
integral part of the industrial transformation strategy.
</P>
<P>
Mwencha pointed out that growth with equity will also require
both macro-economic stability and a selectively targeted supply side
intervention between member governments, the private sector and civil
society.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, which now groups 20 members, is designed to achieve a full
free trade area in the sub-region by 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
