<HEADLINE> Africans to Better Cooperate in Leather Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Leather and Leather Products
Institute (LLPI) of the Common Market for Southern and Eastern
Africa (COMESA) and the Eastern and Southern Africa Leather
Industries Association (ESALIA) promised to enhance their
cooperation Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a memorandum of understanding singed here, LLPI Director
Robert Arunga said COMESA has attached great importance to the
development of leather and leather products industries in the
region.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need to develop the sector through the
involvement of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
He said with signing of the memorandum of understanding, the
two associations will cooperate in areas of human resources
development, cmnsultancy and information services.
</P>
<P>
Arunga said the objective of LLPI mainly is to develop the
leather industry fully and provide a linkage to other industries
like chemical and engineering, and in the end create employment
and good incomes to the people in the region.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the joint action will promote the use of
available resources in the region which provides for 60.9 percent
of the cattle population in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Head of the ESALIA Secretariat Samuel Kiruthu said his
association was born out of urgent need to have a coordinated
approach in charting out short and long-term development
strategies for Africa's leather industry.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the signing of memorandum of
understanding will mark a new beginning in the development of
leather.  
</P>
</TEXT>
