<HEADLINE> Kocharyan Wins in Armenia's Presidential Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The Central Elections Commission of
Armenia Wednesday evening confirmed that the results of Armenia's
presidential election showed that Rober Kocharyan has won in the
second round of presidential election, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported from Yerevan.
</P>
<P>
Kocharyan, the acting prime minister, gained 59.48 percent of
the vote, while his rival Karen Demirchyan, the Soviet-era
Communist leader, gained 40.29 percent.
</P>
<P>
A Commission official was quoted as saying that 93 percent of
ballot papers have been processed.
</P>
<P>
Under the Armenian constitution the Central Elections
Commission should sum up the final results of the presidential
elections before next Monday, and publish the results the other
day, then Rober Kocharyan will be officially announced as the
elected president.
</P>
<P>
The Armenian parliament Wednesday made a decision to convene a
special meeting in Yerevan opera house on April 9, where the
elected president will take an oath of office.
</P>
<P>
Former Armenian president Levon Ter-Petrosyan announced his
resignation on February 4, forced by a political crisis over the
settlement of the Nargorno-Karabakh problem.
</P>
<P>
The first round of the presidential elections was held on March
16, when 16 candidates took part in the elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
