<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leoneans Urged to Co-operate With ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The West African Peacekeeping Force
known as ECOMOG Wednesday strongly adviced Sierra Leoneans to respect
orders from ECOMOG and police in order to maintain social security in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, made by ECOMOG Task Force Commander Maxwell Kobe,
followed Tuesday's shooting by ECOMOG soldiers which badly wounded a
middle-aged man in central Freetown, the capital of S. Leone.
</P>
<P>
A British Broadcasting Corporation report quoted eye-witnesses as
saying that the man was shot while going to the State House in
defiance of the order to stop at an ECOMOG security checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
The warning shot was fired in the air and the second shot hit the
passerby in the leg.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging the shooting incident, Kobe urged all Sierra
Leoneans to follow the orders from the sub-regional force and police,
which are trying to bring some forms of order of law to the country
after more than nine months of chaos caused by last May's coup.
</P>
<P>
Kobe said indiscipline does not go with security, especially
when the country is under the state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
During the debate on the state of emergency earlier, the members of
parliament said that Sierra Leoneans were very confused over the issue
of their safety and security after more than 5,000 junta soldiers and
the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) rebels had been disposed of their
weapons and allowed to go home and do things as usual.
</P>
<P>
Many people believe that this is a serious issue, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, ECOMOG has started the manning of the
security checkpoints again around the city.
</P>
<P>
These checkpoints were dismantled according to the ECOMOG High
Command to give some semblance of normalcy in the capital.
</P>
<P>
But with thousands of former soldiers and RUF rebels still at large
and apparently echoing the sentiment of the people, Kobe's
decision to re-man the checkpoints has been well welcomed, the
report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
