<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-01 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Speaker Rejects Israeli Pullout Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Parliament Speaker Nabih
Berry Wednesday rejected Israel's inner cabinet decision on
conditional withdrawal from south Lebanon, saying there is nothing
new in the Israeli move.
</P>
<P>
Berry made the remark when meeting with parliament members. He
said that Israel's acceptance of the U.N. Security Council
resolution 425 can be interpreted as a political preparation for
Israeli forces to launch new attacks in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday morning Israel's inner cabinet approved, with
conditions attached, the 20-year-old U.N. resolution 425 calling
for unconditional Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that Israel showed willingness, of a
sort, to comply with this U.N. resolution over the past two
decades since it first invaded Lebanon in 1978.
</P>
<P>
But it remained stubborn in linking execution of the resolution
with negotiated security arrangements with Lebanese government in
the area it wanted to quit because of heavy casualties, a
condition strongly rejected by Lebanon and its close ally, Syria.
</P>
<P>
The demanded arrangements include deploying Lebanese
government troops in the south, disarming the Iranian-backed
resistance Hezbollah, or Party of God, and integrating the
pro-Israeli militia South Lebanese Army (SLA), in the Lebanese
regular forces.
</P>
<P>
When Israel first hinted it might go along with the
U.N. resolution at the start of this year, Lebanon and Syria,
whose 40,000 troops are stationed in Lebanon, insisted that the
resolution must be implemented unconditionally and without
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Israel has grown anxious to pull itself out of the quagmire in
south Lebanon where it was engaged in an attrition war with
Hezbollah with increasing losses of lives.
</P>
<P>
By announcing the proposal, Israel also wanted to impress the
world at large that the peace wheel in the Middle East, stalled as
it is on many fronts, still keeps moving on the Israeli-Lebanese
track.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic resistance Hezbollah is spearheading a guerrilla
war against an estimated 1,200-strong Israeli forces, aided by the
2,500-strong SLA, which have been occupying south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in 1985
after two invasions of south Lebanon, allegedly to protect
Israel's northern areas from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
