<HEADLINE> Egypt, PNA See Eye to Eye on U.S. Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) see eye to eye on the latest U.S. initiative to
save the Mideast peace process, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt and the Palestinians have reached consensus on the
recent U.S. proposal to resume the Palestinian and Israeli talks,
and will follow up its development," Moussa told reporters in
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came after Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and PNA
President Yasser Arafat met in the Red Sea resort of Sharm
el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will boost their sustained coordinations in the
future as regards their next steps following the U.S. proposals,
he said, quoted by the Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Arafat flew to Sharm el-Sheikh Tuesday night to brief Mubarak
on the results of his three rounds of talks last week with
U.S. Middle East peace mediator Dennis Ross who brought with him a
new U.S. initiative to restart the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Washington wants Israel to withdraw from 13.1 percent of the
West Bank in exchange for Palestinian security cooperation as part
of a package deal to end a year-long Mideast peace stalemate. The
idea, however, bounced by the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Egypt said earlier that it was ready to cooperate with the
U.S. peace-saving efforts so long as they advocates "balanced
peace" in the region.
</P>
<P>
Ross, who met Mubarak and Moussa in Egypt Monday, is expected
to present a report to President Bill Clinton and Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on his failed mission.
</P>
<P>
Washington has threatened to remove from the Middle East peace
process as a mediator in an attempt to put pressure to bear on
Israel and the Palestinians to make compromises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
