<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Up, Paris Hits New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
sustained Tuesday's rally and ended higher Wednesday, supported by
a firm dollar and the start of the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE-100 index on the London market closed up 85.4 points
or 1.44 percent at 6,017.6, above the psychological 6,000 mark for
the first time, boosted by a wave of buyers at the start of the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
But the index failed to hang on to its best levels as a weak
opening on Wall Street prompted a mild retreat.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that index futures-led derivatives trading and
stock shortages also fueled the gains.
</P>
<P>
The Paris CAC-40 index also ended well off the day's earlier
highs on a disappointing start of the Dow, but managed to rise to
a second consecutive record close, up 7.5 points or 0.19 percent
at 3,883.31.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that a strong dollar and another set of strong
corporate earnings, from construction and communications group
Bouygues, helped carry shares higher.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, Germany's DAX-30 index had earlier hit a fresh
record high of 5,170.29 before ending off the day's peak at
5,154.21, but still up 51.86 points or 1.02 percent, driven by the
strength of the dollar and sharp gains in financials. 
</P>
