<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Welcomes Israel Withdrawal Decision from Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright on Wednesday welcomed Israel's decision to withdraw its
troops from south Lebanon and called for talks between Israel and
Lebanon on the issue.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the decision by the Israeli Cabinet. This is a
positive step," Albright said after talks with Qatar's foreign
minister Sheik Hamad bin Jasim al-Thani.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Cabinet on Wednesday adopted the 20-year-old U.N.
Security Council resolution 425, which called for a unilateral
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon five days after Israel
invaded Lebanon in 1978 to wipe out Palestinian guerrilla bases.
</P>
<P>
"We have supported resolution 425 and therefore are pleased
that the Israeli Cabinet took this action," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu set a condition
for the withdrawal, demanding Lebanon to deploy its troops
southward to prevent cross-border guerrilla attacks on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Lebanese leaders dismissed the Israeli move,
calling the condition a "new obstacle" to peace. Lebanese
President Elias Krawi said the Israeli offer was a trial balloon
and said Israel must withdraw from Lebanon unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Albright said it is important that "some discussions" would
be needed if the withdrawal was to take place.
</P>
<P>
"I think some discussions between Israel and Lebanon on this,
in order to assure that the northern border of Israel is indeed
secure," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-01 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM on Cyprus' EU Accession Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides said here Wednesday that with the start of Cyprus'
accession talks with the European Union (EU), the prospects for a
Cyprus settlement can be bright.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides made the remark upon his return from Brussels, where
he attended the official opening of EU's membership talks on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He described the Cyprus-EU accession talks as the most
positive element since Turkey's military intervention in the
island in 1974, saying that there is no question of delaying
Cyprus' entry under the present circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"No country entered accession talks without success,"
Kasoulides said, stressing that the EU would not allow for such
talks to begin if it judged an applicant country not in a position
to conclude them successfully.
</P>
<P>
He said there would be a lot of movement this month concerning
efforts for a solution to the Cyprus problem and the government
welcomes envoys of all willing foreign governments to contribute
to breaking the present deadlock in the peace process on the
island.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special advisor Diego
Cordovez recently visited the island and held talks with the
leaders of the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities, but was
unable to secure an agreement on resumption of stalled talks aimed
at reuniting the divided island.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash, who met Annan and
Cordovez in Geneva last Saturday, said the peace talks in Cyprus
can no longer take place on an inter-communal basis but between
independent states.
</P>
<P>
This implies recognition of the breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus", proclaimed in 1983 but recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said "the position of the (Cypriot) government has
always been that the work of the U.N. secretary-general should be
assisted by the five permanent members of the Security Council,
either together or separately."
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the Cypriot government had no information
concerning a forthcoming visit of U.S. presidential emissary
Richard Holbrooke to the island.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus News Agency Wednesday quoted diplomatic sources as
saying that Holbrooke and State Department Special Coordinator for
Cyprus Thomas Miller are expected to arrive in Cyprus in the next
couple of days.
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. officials are expected to have meetings with
President Glafcos Clerides and Denktash, the news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
