<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes Hard on African Peacekeeping Force  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LAGOS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton of the United

States Wednesday repeatedly sought support for the U.S.-initiated plan

security in Africa.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to the Senegalese military airbase in Thies, 70

km east of the capital Dakar, Clinton said the force would rapidly

respond to wars and refugee crisis, bringing "security, hope and a

future" to Africa.
</P>
<P>
U.S. army special forces are training Senegales troops in Thies to

participate in the African crisis response initiative put forward by

the U.S. government two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, troops in Senegal, Uganda and Malawi have been

trained by soldiers from the 3rd Special Forces Group of the U.S.

army, while Malian troops are undergoing their own training.
</P>
<P>
The training of Ghanaian troops is scheduled to begin Wednesday

and Ethoipia has also signed up for the training.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Clinton said#,an African crisis response force

is "very important" for the peace and security in the continent,

an issue which is both a key part of his first ever African visit as

president and the major topic in the discussion between him and his

Senegalese counterpart President Abdou Diouf.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and other African countries have expressed "more or

less" interest in participanting but insisted the force will have an

African command in charge.
</P>
<P>
A total force of 10,000 to 12,000 is envisaged though the U.S.

is doubtful this many troops would ever be called at one time.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Africa's economic giant Nigeria, which is out of

Clinton's itinerary, has said it's better that such a force has the

west African peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG as nuclues.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian-led ECOMOG has successfully put an end to civil wars

in Liberia and Sierra Leone, providing somewhat of a model to the

international community.
</P>
<P>
According to Clinton, the U.S. wants to build on existing efforts

including those of African countries, the Organization of African

Unity, the United Nations, France, Britain and others to strengthen

the capacity for preseving peace in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Our purpose is not to dominate seucrity matters in Africa or to

abandon America's role in Africa's security," said Clinton, who a week

ago admitted the U.S. and others reacted too slowly to stop Rwanda's

1994 genocide which led to the slaughter of more than 500,000 Tutsis

and Hutus.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has promised the U.S. will provide assistance and training

in order for African countries to conduct their own peacekeeping

exercises on their own continent, saying such a force will relieve the

U.S. forces of having to intervene in African problems.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president arrived in Dakar Tuesday night for a two-day

visit. In the past week or more, he visited Ghana, Uganda, Rwanda,

South Africa and Botswana, in a bid to promote new partnership

relations with Africa.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the need to preserve peace and security in Africa,

Clinton announced that he would send three of his cabinet ministers to

Africa as follow-up to promote trade and economic ties with the

world's poorest continent.
</P>
<P>
However, some African leaders have rejected the U.S. attempt to

lay down pre-conditions for assistance to African countries.
</P>
<P>
South African President Nelson Mandela has said: "We oppose any

attempt by any country to impose conditions on our freedom of trade

and that we cannot accept."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
