<HEADLINE> German Socialist Leader Pledges to Keep Ties With France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- German Social Democratic leader
Gerhard Schroeder Wednesday pledged to keep the special ties
between Germany and France if he becomes the next German
chancellor later this year.
</P>
<P>
"We all agree that the French-German relations are
irreplaceable and indispensable for Europe. It is a relationship
which should be maintained," said Schroeder after meeting with
French Socialist Party First Secretary Francois Hollande.
</P>
<P>
As for his attitude toward the European single currency, the
minister-president of the German state of Lower Saxony said that
it is no longer necessary to argue about the reason for launching
the single currency, as it is already "a part of history."
</P>
<P>
He said what is important now is to discuss "how to maximize
the chances and minimize the risks" in adopting the euro.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder was criticized by some French officials for
expressing his doubt over the advantages the euro can bring about,
and for suggesting that the French-German axis is not as good as a
German-British-French triangle alliance in European construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
