<HEADLINE> Botswana's New President Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Festus Mogae was sworn in
Wednesday as the third president of the Republic of Botswana, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
In a speech after his inauguration, Mogae pledged to tackle
Botswana's poverty and high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Botswana's official unemployment is now 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
"I pledge to continue to work to promote private sector development
and to engage constructively with the labor representatives to achieve
poverty alleviation through employment creation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mogae, 58, promised a pragmatic approach to economic management and
the maintenance of an open economy in an open society.
</P>
<P>
"I commit to the national principles of democracy, development,
self-reliance and national unity," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mogae replaced the long-serving Ketumile Masire, who stepped down
at midnight Tuesday in a smooth transition of power.
</P>
<P>
Masire, 72, had ruled Botswana for 18 years. Mogae also named a new
line-up Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
