<HEADLINE> Irish Police Intercept Huge Car Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Irish police said Thursday that
they intercepted a bomb in a Britain-bound car at a ferry port
near Dublin which contained nearly half a ton of home-made
explosive, boosters, detonators and a timer, adding that it was
the work of republican guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Media reports here said that it was among the biggest bombs
Irish police had ever found.
</P>
<P>
Chief superintendent Patrick Culhane was quoted as saying that
"some element of republican paramilitaries" was believed to be
behind it.
</P>
<P>
Police also confirmed that two BMW cars were involved in the
apparent bid to launch a terrorist attack on the UK.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the vehicles were stopped as they queued
in the port of Dun Laoghaire near Dublin for a ferry bound for
Anglesey on the Welsh coast.
</P>
<P>
Five people, including two women, are being questioned by
detectives.
</P>
<P>
The incident came at a particularly sensitive time for the
Northern Irish peace talks as there is not much time left before
the April 9 deadline to hammer out an agreement.
</P>
<P>
However, the participants of the peace talks are still divided
on several issues, particularly on the power of a new North-South
administration which is supposed to be set up under the peace
deal.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish
counterpart Bertie ]hern Thursday reportedly said after three
hours of a late-night talk in London Wednesday that "more work
needs to be done" in the search for peace and there were still
hurdles to overcome.
</P>
<P>
However, Blair's spokesman said Thursday that the Prime
Minister remains "cautiously, stubbornly optimistic" about
prospects for a breakthrough in the Northern Irish peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
