<HEADLINE> UN to Hold Conference on S. Leone Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations will soon hold
a conference in Sierra Leone's capital, Freetown, on
international assistance in rebuilding the war-devastated
country.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Thursday here at a press conference by
Zimbabwean Voreign Minister Stan Mudenge who led a five-men
Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) team this week to
assess the needs of the reinstated government of President Tejan
Kabbah, which was ousted last May in a military coup.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge said the conference would focus mainly on assisting
the country to rebuild its institutions.
</P>
<P>
"In that respect on our visit we agreed with President Kabbah
that the commonwealth develop and implement support for the
development of a sound policy framework for the country's mining
sector," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also agreed that commonwealth countries should
support the rebuilding of Sierra Leone's national institutions
such as the police, he added.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether Zimbabwe was going to help, Mudenge said, "If
asked to help there would not be any problem. I think we can do
that as we did with South Africa when they requested for help in
rebuilding their police."
</P>
<P>
"We also urged all member governments to assist bilaterally in
every practicable way in the country's efforts to achieve
national reconstruction and reconciliation," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
