<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Judge Comments On Chinese Court Procedure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Dorothy Nelson, a prestigious
judge in the United States' Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals, who is
visiting Kunming, capital of southwest China's Yunnan Province,
said today that the mediation used by Chinese courts is a method
that American judges could study.
</P>
<P>
Judge Nelson arrived in Beijing late last month and has visited
to courts and held discussions with judges in the cities of
Beijing and Hangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Chinese judges often try to get the two parties involved in a
lawsuit to reach a consensus, and about 60 percent of all lawsuits
are concluded in this way.
</P>
<P>
In some ways, this is a better method than that used in the
United States, where judges have to rule on many trivial things,
but mediation can make people accept the consensus more agreeably,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, she expressed the hope that China's judiciary will
not make the same errors or mistakes American courts have in
expecting every lawsuit to be decided by a court ruling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Champion to Play against Top-rated female Player </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 2 (Xinhua) -- World chess champion Anatoly
Karpov will play eight speed matches against the world's top-rated
female player Judit Polgar of Hungary, according to local reports
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The matches will take place from June 9 to 12 in Budapest, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
Karpov is the reigning champion of the World Chess Federation,
but his fellow Russian Garry Kasparov is considered the true world
champion.
</P>
<P>
Karpov defended his title against Viswanathan Anand of India in
January.
</P>
<P>
