<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Relaxes Use of Transit Route By Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- India has agreed to relax some
conditions to make the operation of the Phulbari transit route
easier for Nepal, press reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting between Indian commerce secretary and his
Nepalese counterpart in New Delhi on Monday and Tuesday, India
agreed to make an arrangement for Nepal to use the transit route
four days a week instead of two days a week as set under previous
modalities.
</P>
<P>
India also agreed to allow transportation of goods by container
or by truck with seals by the Indian customs at the entry point to
make sure that the goods are not tampered with midway, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the trucks and containers must be escorted by the
Indian security force.
</P>
<P>
Commerce secretaries of the two countries also discussed a
seven-year-old transit treaty which expires late this year and
decided that separate bilateral talks will be held in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The Phulbari transit route, which gives Nepal an access to the
Mongla port in Bangladesh through Phulbari in northeastern India,
went into operation on September 1, 1997 on a six-month trial
basis.
</P>
<P>
But except a convoy of trucks on the inauguration day, no other
trucks used the route in the past seven months. Impractical
modalities were mainly blamed for the poor use.
</P>
<P>
Early in March, India extended Nepal's use of the route and
agreed to review the modalities when commerce secretaries of the
two countries met in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to Nepal in mid-March, Bangladeshi Finance
Minister Shah Kibria said that his country would take measures to
upgrade the physical infrastructure in Bangladesh to make the
transit route economically viable in the near future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
