<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Moves Toward Curbing Hazardous Chemicals: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide governments are to meet
in Montreal in June over a draft treaty that will minimize the
release of persistent organic pollutants (POPs) into the
environment, the U.N. Environment Program (UNEP) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The talks, scheduled for June 29, will start with a list of 12
POPs including some of the most toxic chemicals ever developed,
said a statement issued at a press conference in the UNEP
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The total negotiations are expected to be completed by 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Thousands of people are killed or seriously poisoned by toxic
pesticides and chemicals every year," said UNEP chief Klaus
Topfer in the statement, stressing hazardous chemicals a top
priority for global environment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he called for further concerted international
action as no country acting alone can protect its environment
from risk since chemicals circulate globally -- whether through
trade or naturally via air, water and animals.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to the deaths and acute effects caused by direct
and immediate contact, POPs and other chemicals persist for years
at background levels that can cause long-term damage to human
health and the environment," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The situation is further worsening due to the accumulation of
unwanted and obsolete stockpiles of pesticides and toxic
chemicals, particularly in developing countries, since 1950s,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Dump sites and toxic drums dated from 1950s are now decaying
and leaching chemicals into the soil and thus poisoning water
resources, wildlife and people, it said.
</P>
<P>
A great deal of infrastructure and equipment such as
electrical transformers and capacitors are also at or near the
end of their useful lives and are leaking dangerous chemicals, it
warned.
</P>
<P>
With worldwide sales of some 1.5 trillion U.S. Dollars
annually, the chemicals industry is a vital part of the
international modern industrial economy and continues to expand
its size currently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
