<HEADLINE> Movie Blockbuster `Titanic' Chugs into China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The blockbuster movie "Titanic"
has began its Chinese run in the country's capital.
</P>
<P>
Starting tomorrow, every major Chinese city will be showing the
movie which has caused a worldwide sensation and earned more than
1 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Managers of some Beijing cinemas said that tickets have already
sold out, and they expect the film will set box office records,
easily beating "The Lost World."
</P>
<P>
"Titanic" has been front-paged many Chinese newspapers since
last month, with a host of reports citing its remarkable
investment, superb digital technology and marvelous acting
skills. Some say that the movie's love story theme will touch the
hearts of Chinese viewers.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the China Film Corp. said this is the shortest
time span for a movie to hit the Chinese market after it won the
Oscar prize for best movie.
</P>
<P>
The film, based on a true incident, won 11 Oscars last month.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the China Film Corp. began to discuss the
possibility of introducing the film early this year with 20th
Century Fox and Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, China has adopted a policy of sharing
the benefits with major international film companies after
releasing their movies on the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
The move intends to satisfy Chinese viewers who have not felt
contented with so many domestic movies.
</P>
<P>
Many people in China know at least a little about the Titanic
story. And Titanic books emerged on bookstores across the country
overnight before the film was shown.  
</P>
</TEXT>
