<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rice Stock to Reach 2.2 mln Tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's rice stock this year
could reach 2.2 million tons, enough to meet the country's demand
up to the end of the year, an official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"People should not be worried about food shortage," National
Logistics Agency (Bulog) Chairman Beddu Among said.
</P>
<P>
Among made the remark in response to a survey made by the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) showing that some 7.5
million people in Indonesia's 15 provinces will experience food
scarcity if drought continues this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the UNDP, the country's rice production in the
next few months will also be low and that Indonesia is expected to
import food commodities in large volume in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Among said that considering last year's EL Nino that badly
affected Indonesia's crops, Bulog's rice supply still reached 1.95
million tons.
</P>
<P>
"That will be easier to surpass this year," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, Bulog will remain vigilant about the
possibility of food scarcity as some regions are already
experiencing now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
