<HEADLINE> Hungary's Tourism Income Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Hungary's tourism industry saw a
15 percent increase in foreign exchange earnings in 1997 despite a
slump in the number of foreign tourist arrivals in the year.
</P>
<P>
The foreign exchange income of the central European nation
stood at 2.58 billion U.S. dollars, making a favorable balance of
1.43 billion dollars, an 11 percent rise from a year before,
latest bank figures indicated.
</P>
<P>
Foreign visitors to Hungary totaled 37.32 million last year,
down 6.3 percent from 1996, according to the National Bank of
Hungary.
</P>
<P>
The slump was mainly blamed on the fall in the number of
tourist arrivals from eastern European nations, such as Ukraine,
Russia and Romania.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the number of tourists from western European
countries, such as Germany, Italy and France, grew steadily,
boosting the rise in tourism earnings.
</P>
<P>
The country's tourism foreign exchange earnings in 1998 is
expected to amount to 2.8 to 3 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
