<P>
The daily newspaper reported that she has with immediate
effect banned the workshops in her ministry for the next three
months because most of them are fruitless as their resolutions
are never implemented.
</P>
<P>
Luo, who was named as the country's new health minister last
month, imposed the ban when she addressed a community partnership
in health workshop held in Livingstone in southern Zambia
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
She said now is the time for implementation and not planning,
adding that she will personally go round the country to inspect
whether workshop resolutions are implemented.
</P>
<P>
Luo warned health workers to sit up and take work seriously or
risk being sacked for incompetence.
</P>
<P>
She warned workers against laziness and told those unable to
perform to step aside.
</P>
<P>
The new minister cautioned once again health workers not to
join unions that do not promote health ethics and
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
But the Civil Servants Union of Zambia (CSUZ) advised the
health workers to join any union of their choice and ignore Luo's
advice.
</P>
<P>
CSUZ General Secretary Japhet Moonde said here Thursday that
"workers under the ministry of health have the right to belong to
a union of their choice just like ordinary Zambians have the
right to belong to a political party of their own choice."
