<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. African Coup Report Dismissed as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A South African military
intelligence report alleging that senior African National
Congress (ANC) members were plotting a coup was fraudulent, a
judicial commission probing the matter has found.
</P>
<P>
The report, handed to President Nelson Mandela in February by
South African National Defense Force (SANDF) Chief George
Meiring, had "no substance" and its handling had been flawed,
according to the commission's report presented to Mandela
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela would brief the senior leadership of the SANDF
Thursday about the contents of the commission's report, and urge
them to speedily address the "glaring shortcomings" in the
handling of the report, a presidential spokesman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said Mandela would soon make public a decision on the
matter after studying the recommendations by the judicial
commission.
</P>
<P>
The government on Wednesday described the report, which hit
newspaper headlines at the weekend, as the work of certain
military elements whose motives were to sow seeds of confusion.
</P>
<P>
Although the people compiling the false report were still not
known, suspicions are running high that right-wing generals
unhappy with the ANC government played a part in its compilation.
</P>
<P>
Mandela appointed a commission last Friday, consisting of
Chief Justice Ismail Mohammed and two Constitutional Court
judges, to investigate urgently "the compilation, verification
and subsequent treatment" of a report handed to him on February
5.
</P>
<P>
The report claimed that Mandela's ex-wife Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela, former ANC member and now United Democratic
Movement co-leader Bantu Holomisa, suspended Foreign Affairs
official Robert McBride, SANDF Chief of Staff Siphiwe Nyanda and
other senior ANC members were plotting to overthrow the
government.
</P>
<P>
It was suspected that Meiring, who was expected to retire next
year, tried to extend his time in power by implicating his
probable successor, Nyanda, in the alleged plot.
</P>
<P>
The judicial commission worked throughout the weekend calling
witnesses from the SANDF and the government, including Meiring
and other senior officials.
</P>
<P>
Meiring had reportedly failed to explain to the commission on
a number of issues, including why the report was based on a
single resource, it bypassed official intelligence structures and
it was leaked to the media.
</P>
<P>
He had denied taking part in the compilation of the report and
said he handed the report directly to Mandela without subjecting
it to the normal intelligence checks because it was "too
sensitive".
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the SANDF had made attempts to confirm the
contents of the report but had failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
The report, which Meiring did not show to his political head,
Defense Minister Joe Modise, was believed to be compiled from
information given by Vusi Mbatha, a now exposed intelligence
informer and the man arrested with McBride in Mozambique for
alleged gun smuggling in early March.
</P>
<P>
Media reports quoted sources close to the government as saying
that Mandela and Deputy President Thabo Mbeki have agreed to fire
Meiring as well as Police Commissioner George Fivaz, who was
involved in the dissemination of the report.
</P>
<P>
The government said with the 1999 general elections drawing
near, it was possible that elements wanting to destabilize the
government would try to launch a disinformation campaign.
</P>
<P>
These elements wanted to destabilize the government not only
militarily but economically, it said, warning that it would be
"naive" to narrow down the destabilization tactics to military
intelligence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
