<HEADLINE> Philippine NDF Rebels Consider Ceasefire With Govt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The National Democratic Front (NDF)
rebel group is considering a ceasefire with Philippine government
troops, local Television Station PTV reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said Jose Sison, the founding chairman of the NDF,
is mulling over the cessation of hostilities between government
troops and the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Luis Jalandoni, a senior leader and
representative of the NDF, arrived here from the Netherlands to
negotiate with President Fidel Ramos for the release of all
political prisoners as one of the final steps for the proposed
ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
Jalandoni said Sison, who has been in exile for more than 20
years in Hague, the Netherlands, will come back to Manila if the
government will assure his safety and "if all political prisoners
will be freed."
</P>
<P>
Philippine Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat said he would
guarantee the safety and peaceful stay of Sison and his party once
he returns to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government has been in peace talks with the NDF
for the past three years. However, the two sides made little
progress in reaching a full ceasefire, let alone a final peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
President Ramos announced a unilateral ceasefire with the NDF
on March 31 to ensure that the May 11 elections would be held
peacefully and the NDF rebels can participate in the polls.
</P>
