<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Flights to War-Torn S. Sudan Resumed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Relief flights resumed Thursday
to all areas of OBhr El Ghazal Province in war-torn Sudan where a
severe famine is looming, after the Khartoum government turned on
a green light last month.
</P>
<P>
The lift came at a critical moment when about 350,000 people
are in need of urgent humanitarian assistance especially food and
medicine, said a news release from the Operation Lifeline Sudan
(OLS) issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Many people in southern Sudan are currently surviving on wild
foods and the malnutrition rate among children is rising, said
the OLS, coordinator for most of the international relief
operations in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Food aid deliveries and urgent supplies of seed and tools are
particularly essential over the next four weeks when people are
cultivating their land before the rains arrive and in preparation
for the next harvest, said OLS.
</P>
<P>
If the next harvest is missed, the Sudanese people will be
reliant on relief food for survival until August 1999, it warned.
</P>
<P>
The new clearance now allows OLS agencies to fly in April to
more than 50 locations in Bahr El Ghazal, and to 180 countrywide,
the highest number of approved locations since June 1997.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC)
in Lokichokio, a town 25 kilometers south of Sudan border, told
Xinhua last week that ICRC was also planning to re-start its
relief flights to southern Sudan in mid April.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government suspended all flights into Bahr El
Ghazal on February 4 following the outbreak of fightings around
the town of Wau.
</P>
<P>
The ban was partially eased three weeks later and further
lifted in mid March thanks to the mediation of Robert van Schaik,
U.N. envoy for humanitarian affairs in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
OLS, set up ten years ago, remains the only official channel
through which assistance can be delivered to both government and
rebel locations throughout Sudan, the largest African state
plagued by civil war since 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
