<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls on Developed Countries to fulfill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China called on developed
countries Thursday to fulfill their commitment made at the United
Nations Conference on Environment and Development in Rio de
Janeiro six years ago.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the First Assembly of the Global Environment
facility (GEF) in New Delhi, Jin Liqun, Head of the Chinese
delegation, said developed countries, with only a few exceptions,
have been reducing their official development assistance in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The resources available to the GEF are far from adequate to
meet the increasing financial demands for addressing the austere
global environmental reality, Jin told the three-day meeting which
opened on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from 164 member countries and international
organizations attended the assembly which was scheduled to review
the general policies and operations of the GEF in the last seven
years since its founding in 1991.
</P>
<P>
As a fund, the GEF has provided the urgently-needed assistance
to developing countries and enabled them to participate better in
the cause of global environment protection, said Jin, who is
Assistant Minister of Finance.
</P>
<P>
And as a mechanism of international cooperation in the
environment arena, Jin added, the GEF has helped enhance the
awareness of the international community about some of the major
global environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
It has also cemented the concerted efforts of developed and
developing countries and some international institutions to
address the climate change and to protect biodiversity,
international waters and ozone layer.
</P>
<P>
However, Jin said, the GEF can not meet the requirements of its
members due to the reluctance of certain developed countries to
make their donations and fulfill their obligations and commitment.
</P>
<P>
Jin told his audience that the Chinese government attaches
great importance to environment protection and made it one of the
basic state policies in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Jin pointed out, China has made notable progress
in environment protection as well as economic and social
development:
</P>
<P>
-- While registering rapid economic growth, China has basically
been able to avoid drastic environmental degradation, and even
improve the environment in certain areas;
</P>
<P>
-- The family planning program has been implemented
effectively, and the nation's natural population growth rate has
dropped steadily;
</P>
<P>
-- The economic growth pattern has begun to transform, the
emission and discharging standards are been enforced nation wide,
and initial success has been achieved in the implementation of the
Cross-Century Green Project;
</P>
<P>
-- Proactive measures have been taken to preserve biodiversity,
a network of nature reserves has taken shape, and the forest
coverage has risen from less than 13 percent in 1992 to about 14
percent at present as a result of the implementation of
nation-wide voluntary afforestation program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
