<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Loses 256 mln U.S. Dollars in Forest Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Forest fires in East Kalimantan
province, Indonesia, have destroyed at least 150,000 hectares of
forest land, causing an estimated loss of 2.1 trillion rupiah
(about 256 million U.S. dollars), the province's governor said
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I believe it is difficult to extinguish the fires in the near
future," East Kalimantan Governor H. M. Ardans said after
reporting the fires to President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
Ardans said if the rains do not fall until June, the fires will
be even more difficult to extinguish.
</P>
<P>
Another long dry season is expected to start in June, he said.
</P>
<P>
The forest fires, which started in January this year,
originated from 808 hot spots scattered in thick rainforests and
are still razing forests in the province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, a local official said the fires had caused as much
material damage as the total losses from sporadic forest fires in
the province over the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
East Kalimantan has 21 million hectares of forests, including
17 million hectares of productive forests and 4 million hectares
of virgin forests.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a United Nations disaster team, which arrived here a
few days ago, will soon travel to the fire-ravaged East Kalimantan
province to assess the scale of damage and see what relief efforts
are needed, official sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Last year, at least 300,000 hectares of forests were ravaged by
fires in Sumatra and Kalimantan islands in Indonesia. In East
Kalimantan province fires destroyed 37,092 hectares of forests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
