<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Dowry Makes Marriage Evil Dream in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Malati Devi, a mother of two
kids, was beaten to death by her husband and father-in-law simply
because she could not afford a TV set as a dowry.
</P>
<P>
Ever since she got married in 1993, Devi's husband and
father-in-law had been demanding for a TV set as a dowry. But her
poor family could not meet their demand. This February, her
husband and father-in-law managed to buy a TV set by selling her
ornaments. When she protested, they beat her to death. Her second
daughter was only 22 days old.
</P>
<P>
Chandra Kala, mother of one kid, did not know her parents had
agreed to build a house for her husband as a dowry when she got
married three years before. When her parents failed, severe
physical torture became part of her daily life. In this February,
her husband and mother-in-law poured kerosene on her in a closed
room and burnt her to death.
</P>
<P>
The stories are just two of the often-heard-of tragedies
carried in the Kathmandu Post daily. Dowry, as a social custom,
has been a major threat to the dream of happy marriage of a lot of
Nepalese women and even to their lives.
</P>
<P>
"It's a social custom, but an evil custom actually," said Dr.
Krishna B. Bhattachan, a sociologist of the Tribhuvan University
of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
There is also a hierarchy in the dowry system in the Nepali
society. Dr. Bhattachan said if somebody is illiterate and poor,
he asks for around 5,000-10,000 rupees (about 80-160 U.S.
dollars). If he receives high school education and is poor, he
might ask for 10,000-50,000 rupees (160-800 dollars).
</P>
<P>
While a college graduate who has a job might demand more than
100,000 rupees (1,600 dollars), a guy with a master degree or a
doctor degree who has a job will ask for 1 million rupees (16,000
dollars) and a doctor of medicine will demand 1 to 2 million
rupees (16,000-32,000 dollars) in cash in addition to commodities
which usually include TV set, car, video cassette recorder,
motorcycle and refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
The more education one receives and the better job he has, the
more dowry he will demand for.
</P>
<P>
Of late a dowry-related story appeared in the Kathmandu Post.
It goes that a newly married engineer threatened his father-in-law
that he did not get enough dowry and wanted more. But his
father-in-law turned down his request. Then the engineer broke
into his father-in-law's home and seriously injured his
brother-in-law and sister-in-law with a sword.
</P>
<P>
The dowry system is evil in many aspects, according to Dr.
Bhattachan. First, it strains the relations between the bride and
her family members including her husband. A bride's status in her
new family depends on the dowry, but she is not treated well even
if she takes a large amount of dowry with her. If demand for more
is not met, her husband and other family members will resort to
violence. The cases of dowry-related deaths have been increasing
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Due to the heavy burden of dowry, boys are preferred in Nepal.
It was reported that among the indigenous communities in Terai,
the birth of a daughter is regarded as a curse while the birth of
a son seen as a boon.
</P>
<P>
Every one would agree that the dowry system is bad. But Dr.
Bhattachan said that other big problems like illiteracy, lack of
infrastructure and poverty sideline the issue of dowry. Now the
government is well aware of the problem and has been making
efforts to minimize violence against women.
</P>
<P>
Dharani Dhar Khatiwada, secretary at the Ministry of Women and
Social Welfare, told Xinhua the other day that his ministry sees
the dowry system as a "remnant of feudal social values" which is
hindering the development of women.
</P>
<P>
He said Nepal has signed the U.N. Convention on Elimination of
All Discrimination Against Women and the ministry has drafted a
bill on domestic violence which is being under discussion. To
raise awareness among people about the unhealthy system, more than
20 seminars have been held in different districts of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Loan For Air-Quality Inspections In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Some 40 million yuan (4.8 million
US dollars) in low interest French loans will be used to build 16
air-quality automatic inspection stations in this Chinese
capital, one of the most heavily polluted cities in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese capital, which boasts approximately 1.3 million
motor vehicles, has eight American air-inspection stations that it
got in 1983. The system is generally used for five years in the
US, but it has been in operation for 15 years, thanks to the
efforts of city technicians.
</P>
<P>
The 16 new stations are allowed to allow the city to make air
quality reports daily, instead of weekly as it does now, which
will help boost the city's image as an international metropolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
