<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Links Withdrawal from Lebanon to Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official said
on Thursday that Israel will not withdraw its troops from south
Lebanon until a security arrangement is reached.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet's decision to endorse the United Nations
resolution 425 and withdraw from Lebanon is linked to a security
arrangement with Lebanon, Israeli Coordinator for Activities
in Lebanon Uri Lubrani told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the Lebanese government should guarantee the security
of Israel's northern areas.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way in which Israel can unilaterally withdraw
without an arrangement," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli inner cabinet on Wednesday approved the
U.N. resolution 425, which calls for an unconditional Israeli
withdraw from south Lebanon. But the Israeli cabinet, meanwhile,
demanded the Lebanese government guarantee the security of the
bordering areas.
</P>
<P>
Lubrani called United States response to Israel's decision "an
important development," saying that it "gave a credibility which
is necessary to get the whole process off the ground."
</P>
<P>
Immediately after Israel approved the U.N. resolution, U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright urged Lebanon to hold talks
with Israel, saying that "discussions between the two parties
would be useful."
</P>
<P>
Lebanon, on its part, has been cool to the Israel's decision,
which it said is a trial balloon. It insisted that the Jewish
state must withdraw from south Lebanon unconditionally under the
U.N. resolution.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Lebanese position, Lubrani said the adoption
of the U.N resolution is just the beginning of a new phase of the
peace process between Israel and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"we need patience" to advance the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to
allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
But Israel has ever since been waging a war of attrition with
Muslim resistance forces. The increasing toll of casualties has
forced the Israeli government to consider withdrawal from south
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
