<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Meets with Japanese Newspaper Publisher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-President Hu Jintao,
in a meeting with Koike Tadao, president of the Japan Publishers
and Editors Association and president of Mainchi Newspapers today,
said that Sino-Japanese relations have made considerable progress
since diplomatic ties were forged.
</P>
<P>
Tadao is here to attend an exhibition of modern Japanese
calligraphy that opened at the Museum of the Chinese Revolution
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Hu mentioned the 20th anniversary of the Treaty of Peace and
Friendship Between the PRC and Japan, and said it should be
treasured because it was not easily gained and embodies the
painstaking efforts of many generations of and of the two
governments and men of insight.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan should face the 21st century from a strategic
height and exert themselves to build a long-term and stable
Sino-Japanese relationship of good neighborliness, he said.
</P>
<P>
Hu said he hopes to strengthen the links and dialogues between
the two nations' youth and to open communications and cooperation
on many levels to pass on Sino-Japanese friendship to future
generations.
</P>
<P>
Tadao recalled his first visit to China in 1972, when the two
countries just normalized diplomatic ties, and said he has since
come to China quite a few times, and every time has been
pleasantly surprised to see the ways that China has developed.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Chairman Jiang Chunyun of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee also met with Tadao and his party this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese are in China at the invitation of the All-China
Youth Federation, which hosted the calligraphy exhibition with
Mainchi Newspapers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
