<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Article Outlines Propellent Role of Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The propellent role of consumption
should be valued, according to an article published in today's
"People's Daily".
</P>
<P>
The article explained that strong consumption advances
production, with weak consumption leading to sluggish production.
</P>
<P>
The article pointed out that commodities valued at over 3
trillion yuan were stockpiled in warehouses across the country
during 1996 due to the lack of buyers. a fact which forced
numerous manufacturing enterprises to either partially or
completely halt production.
</P>
<P>
China's economic growth rate fell from 9.7 percent in 1996 to
8.8 percent in 1997, with the average standard indicator of the
propellent role of consumption to economic growth falling from
54.5 percent in previous years to last year's figure of 34.4
percent, the lowest level during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
China will strive to fulfill 1998 goal for an economic growth
rate of eight percent, and thus it is extremely important to
promote and increase consumption in order to enhance the propellent
role of consumption to economic expansion, according to the
article.
</P>
<P>
Both urban and rural residents have witnessed great
improvements in living standards in recent years, with significant
improvements also recorded in the consumption capacity of
individuals.
</P>
<P>
The article cited State Statistical Bureau information
indicating that food has consumed the lion's share of consumption
expenditures, with urban and rural residents lavishing 46.4
percent and 55.2 percent respectively in terms of total 1997
expenditures for related items. Expenditures for housing,
transportation, telecommunications and services also grew by
varying degrees, but nonetheless accounted for only a small
proportion of total expenditures.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number consumers increased savings rather than
consumption as China forged ahead with various kinds reforms
related to existing medical care, housing and education systems.
</P>
<P>
Various measures, including the introduction of mortgage loans
for private housing, were introduced to promote housing
consumption. However the article noted that very little was
achieved in related efforts.
</P>
<P>
Vast potential exists for substantial growth in individual
consumption, according to the article. It further suggested
increasing consumption will require manufacturers to conduct
extensive market research, introduce needed products, and extend
greater efforts to ensure the distribution system is fully
compatible with consumption policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
