<HEADLINE> China Wants Effective Cooperation With Eureka: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official said here
on Thursday that China wants substantial and effective cooperation
with the Eureka program on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Lilan, minister of Science and Technology, made these
remarks at the "Eureka-Asia International Conference -- A New
Challenge for Economic and Technological Cooperation" seminar
which ended here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"China has been following the Eureka program closely," she told
about 500 audiences including her Portuguese counterpart Mariano
Gago and representatives of European institutions and companies.
"Since its implementation, Eureka has become a program of
international reputation ...It has played an important role in
consolidating the technological innovation capability and
industrial competitiveness of Europe."
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the enterprises and scientific communities of
Europe and Asia could conduct substantial and effective
cooperation in mutually interested areas, on the basis of
equality, mutual benefit and mutual compensation of
advantages," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese minister announced that China has decided that the
four industrial parks in Beijing, Suzhou, Hefei and Xi'an, which
are open to the members of the APEC (Asian-Pacific Economic
Cooperation), will now be open to the members of Eureka.
</P>
<P>
In addition, she proposed that a "Sino-Eureka" seminar be
held at a proper time in Beijing or Europe, so that more
Chinese entrepreneurs and scientists can better know and
participate in the Eureka program.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China is cooperating with Eureka in a project
entitled "Methodology for Analysis of Corrosion Failures in
Maintenance of Industrial Equipment."
</P>
<P>
Started last year, the project is led by Portugal and jointly
undertaken by China, the Netherlands and Brazil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
