<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Turkey Sign MOU to Bolster Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Turkey signed a
Memorandum of Understanding (MOU) here Thursday on measures to
further strengthen the cooperative relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan and his visiting
Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem initialed the document on behalf of
their respective governments, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The MOU envisages increased exchange of visits at all levels,
regular consultations on regional and international issues, closer
coordination in the international fora and increased contacts
between business communities, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, the two countries will also strengthen
cooperation in the fields of energy resources, agriculture and
steel and iron industry, intensify interaction in infrastructure
development and explore possibilities of joint ventures in third
countries, particularly in Central Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the two sides agreed to institutionalize regular
consultations at the level of foreign secretary.
</P>
<P>
The MOU will provide added impetus to multi-dimensional
cooperation already underway between the two brotherly countries,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish foreign minister arrived here Wednesday on a
two-day official visit to Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
