<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Marginally Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
finished the day marginally higher but its early momentum was
sapped by a downturn in the Japanese bourse, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones' Brett O'Donovan said a good night on
Wall Street kicked the Australian market off to a strong start but
it was dragged back by a 500-plus point fall in the Nikkei.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index finished 4.1 points higher at 2757.0,
off an intraday high of 2768.8, with early gains spurred on by the
Dow Jones Industrial Average which closed up 68.76 points at
8,868.32
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was 10.2 points stronger at 4729.3
while the all resources index slipped 1.3 points to 1183.2.
</P>
<P>
Among resource stocks, BHP lost 2.2 cents to 15.41 Australian
dollars, diversified miner WMC shed two, North Ltd closed eleven
lower and Rio Tinto firmed 6.8.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, News Corp was one of the shining
lights, stacking on 30 cents to close. Telstra installment
receipts fell five cents, topping turnover with 16.10 million
receipts changing hands.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector had a mixed day with the bank index gaining
19.7 points to close at 5666.7.
</P>
<P>
ANZ led the charge with a 21 cent surge, while Westpac gained
six cents, the Commonwealth Bank shed 13 and the National
Australia Bank slipped 2.6.
</P>
<P>
More than 13.9 million shares in food group Goodman Fielder
were traded Thursday, with the stock closing four cents lower at
2.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Gold shares had a mixed day with the index closing 1.4 points
higher at 1197.7.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 326.83 million shares traded at a value
of 1.072 billion Australian dollars (707.5 million U.S. dollars),
with falls of 585 beating rises of 421. 
</P>
</TEXT>
