<HEADLINE> Beijing Speeds Up Transportation Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Beijing municipal government
has decided to speed up road-related construction to ease traffic
in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Greater efforts will be made to expedite 12 road-related
projects this year, according to municipal government sources.
</P>
<P>
The No.1 project is Ping'an Avenue, called the "second Chang'an
Avenue." The 6.98-kilometer street now under construction is
expected to be complete within two years at a cost of 3 billion
yuan (361 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second phase of the expressway linking Beijing proper with
the suburban Badaling section of the Great Wall, a famous tourism
spot, should be completed and opened to traffic this year.
</P>
<P>
Other projects include construction of some new roads and
overpasses, and repairing of some overpasses and underground
passages.
</P>
<P>
The city will also invest 2 million yuan in improving local
traffic management systems such as installing automatically
controlled traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
The city will build 15 bus routes, extend 25 bus routes,
lengthen the service time of buses on 40 routes and build 100 bus
stops in addition to putting 700 more buses into service.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
