<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Plans To Prevent Sea Erosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka's Coast Conservation
 Department (CCD) plans to spend 66 million Rs (1.1 million U.S.
dollars) this year to try and solve the problem of sea erosion in
the country, according to the CCD sources here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
About 40,000 square meters is lost annually in Sri Lanka as a
result of sea erosion. Fifty-five percent of the coastal stretch
is now threatened with sea erosion, the sources quoted CCD
Director N. Perera as saying.
</P>
<P>
The CCD had already disbursed money to put up sand pillows and
stone buffers to fight sea erosion, in critically affected areas
like the Southern coast where sea erosion has seriously endangered
coast and villagers have made desperate representation to the
government for action.
</P>
<P>
These would be short to medium term measures as it would
prevent erosion for more than five years, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The CCD need at least 1,200 million Rs (19.7 million U.S.
dollars) to initiate permanent measures, said the sources, adding
that the CCD is currently having talks with the funding agencies,
Asian Development Bank to get money for permanent measures to
prevent erosions in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
