<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Pushed Down by Japanese Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese yen pushed the
Australian dollar lower Thursday following the release of a bleak
business sentiment survey in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The local currency finished at 65.71 U.S. cents, from 66.19
U.S. cents late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar closed on its lows and the U.S.
dollar/Japanese yen went to 133.80 after the Nikkei had a
disappointing fall," Macquarie Bank's Kevin Tuckey said.
</P>
<P>
The Tankan survey of business confidence released by the Bank
of Japan Thursday showed that confidence of major Japanese
companies has suffered a major setback since the last Tankan was
released on December 15.
</P>
<P>
The Tankan's business condition diffusion index (DI) for big
manufacturers - measuring the percentage of companies seeing
conditions improving minus those seeing conditions worsening -
fell to minus 31 from minus 11 in the previous survey.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the survey was further proof Japan's economy
was in recession.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed the local session at 87.82 from
88.37 against Japanese yen, and at 1.2174 from 1.2225 against
Deutsche marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
