<HEADLINE> U.S. Ambassador: Progress Made in Ross Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States has said the
recent mission by its special Mideast envoy Dennis Ross made "a
little progress" in helping break the deadlock in the peace
process, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Ambassador to Cairo Daniel Kurtzer, in a statement to
reporters Wednesday night, rejected claims that Ross has failed to
sell a set of U.S. peace-saving proposals to the Israeli side.
</P>
<P>
"Ross did not return home empty-handed. If we listened and read
what was said by the Israeli leadership, we would not say that
Ross' mission is a failure," he said after talks with Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Kurtzer said he and Moussa exchanged viewpoints on the outcome
of Ross' five-day shuttle mission between Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Ross was trying to bridge the gap between the two sides, he
said, adding that "a little progress has been made."
</P>
<P>
But he did not elaborate on the progress.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said U.S. President Bill Clinton is waiting for
Ross' report on his tour which ended on Monday and would decide
whether to send Ross to the region again.
</P>
<P>
Ross' mission was aimed at selling a U.S. initiative to the
Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Washington reportedly wants Israel to withdraw from 13.1
percent of the West Bank, accompanied by security cooperation of
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But both Israel and the Palestinians were cool to the U.S.
idea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
