<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Jobs Growth to Pick up in Next 6-month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Employment growth was believed to
accelerate in the next six months as an Australian official paper
Thursday showed vacancies climbing back to the highest level in
two years.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) said, total job
vacancies in February 1998 were 71600, an increase of 4.1 percent
from November 1997, and an increase of 14.6 percent from February
1997.
</P>
<P>
According to ABS, the result was the biggest rise in two years
and the 10th consecutive quarterly increase, and the employment
growth was poised to accelerate in the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Private sector job vacancies rose 14.6 percent to their highest
level since the ABS began publishing the series in mid-1979, while
public sector job vacancies fell 12.2 percent for the second
consecutive quarterly decline.
</P>
<P>
All industries reported a rise in vacancies during the quarter
except for accommodation, cafes and restaurants, government
administration and defense, and education.
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Peter Costello said the increase in vacancies showed
job prospects were growing in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"What do you see is the picture of the economy that's emerging:
a low inflation economy with low interest rates and increasing job
opportunities," Costello told parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, Martin Ferguson, spokesman of the opposition on the
employment, said the quarterly rise in vacancies was only a climb
back from the slow jobs growth recorded since the government was
elected in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
