<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coal Stoves Asphyxiate Eleven in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Carbon monoxide fumes from coal
stoves have caused the deaths of eleven people, and sent more than
1,000 people to the hospital over the past four days in the north
China port city of Tianjin, according to government sources.
</P>
<P>
The victims reportedly suffered from carbon monoxide poisoning
resulting from the use of coal stoves during warm spring weather
experienced over the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Abrupt shifts in temperature and barometric pressure
filled homes with carbon monoxide fumes from coal stoves
asphyxiating people while they slept. Changing weather conditions
created an inversion which prevented fumes from escaping through
chimneys.
</P>
<P>
Victims of carbon monoxide poisoning began arriving at Tianjin
hospitals in the early morning hours of March 29. Dozens of the
patients victims exhibited tell-tale symptoms such as vomiting,
unconsciousness and spasms.
</P>
<P>
While most patients recovered following emergency treatment in
hyperbaric oxygen chambers, deaths resulted from some individuals
failing to seek immediate treatment.
</P>
<P>
Half of the families in Tianjin, a city with a population of
over nine million people, heat with coal stove during the winter
season which normally lasts from November to March. Poorly
ventilated homes result in a number of deaths and reported cases of
carbon monoxide poisoning each and every year.
</P>
<P>
However, the most recent cases of carbon monoxide poisoning
represent the worst event of its kind in recent years, according
to a local official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuala Lumpur Stocks Close Sharply Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Share prices on the Kuala
Lumpur Stock Exchange closed lower Thursday in the absence of
potential leads.
</P>
<P>
There was programmed selling from the United States and the
United Kingdom funds as they readjusted and shifted their
portfolios, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The market itself could not find any other leads to help boost
trading amidst concerns on the financial health of local
companies, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the close, the 100-quality stocks Composite Index fell 15.78
points to 684.27, the all-share Emas Index shed 3.96 points to
173.58, the Industrial Index was 14.88 points lower at 1,261.13
and the Second Board Index lost 5.11 points to 170.08.
</P>
<P>
Losers thumped gainers by 677 to 70 while 72 counters were
unchanged and 98 untraded.
</P>
<P>
The day's turnover was 218.342 million shares worth 538.935
million ringgit (144.1 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The main board volume rose to 197.424 million shares valued at
496.872 million ringgit (132.853 million U.S. dollars) from
Wednesday's 150.600 million shares worth 324.521 million ringgit
(86.77 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover was 20.918 million shares valued at
42.062 million ringgit (11.246 million U.S. dollars) against
17.870 million shares worth 40.238 million ringgit (10.758 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals shrank to 9.065 million shares valued at
18.972 million ringgit (5.072 million U.S. dollars) from
Wednesday's 18.991 million shares worth 56.534 million ringgit
(15.116 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
On a sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 9.555
million shares traded, industrial products 14.673 million shares,
construction 18.299 million shares, trading/service 49.014 million
shares, infrastructure 1.105 million shares, finance 44.110
million shares, hotels 639,000 shares, properties 18.456 million
shares, plantations 7.735 million shares, mining 1.806 million
shares, trusts 187,000 shares, closed/fund 98,000 shares and loans
31.747 million shares. 
</P>
