<HEADLINE> China's Lawyers' System Taking Shape, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A new market-oriented legal system
with Chinese characteristics has begun to take shape with lawyers
playing a more active role in society, an official with the
Ministry of Justice said today.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech to mark the second anniversary of the
enactment of the Law of Lawyers, the official said China's current
legal system is the result of nearly 20 years of reform and
improvement.
</P>
<P>
Now, the official said, "the former system dominated by
state-funded law firms has been changed completely, with
non-state-funded firms accounting for 30 percent of the total
number."
</P>
<P>
In addition, most of the state-funded law firms are
self-supporting and self-managed, the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the Ministry of Justice is granting
more management authority to the lawyers association at all levels to
enhance the independence of lawyers.
</P>
<P>
To meet the increasing demand, the Ministry of Justice also
reformed its examination system and now holds a countrywide
examination of lawyers' qualifications every year instead of once
every two years.
</P>
<P>
At present, China has more than 8,300 law firms and 100,000
lawyers, both double the figures five years ago.
</P>
<P>
As an important part of the endeavor to introduce a legal
system, a better system of lawyers will contribute to deepening
China's market-oriented reform, the official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
