<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Supreme Court Rejects Suits Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The German Supreme Court in Karlsruhe
Thursday rejected two suits against Europe's future single currency,
the euro, saying the arguments put forward were clearly unfounded.
</P>
<P>
In one of the suits filed on January 12, four German economics and
law professors argued on constitutional grounds that the euro, with
its stability not guaranteed, would result in high inflation and harm
citizens' property rights.
</P>
<P>
Germany is among one of the 11 European Union states recommended by
the E.U. Commission to launch the euro on January 1, 1999 as planned.
</P>
<P>
Debate is under way in the German parliament which is expected to
decide on April 23-24 on Germany's participation in the euro.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, advocate of the single currency, defended the
euro as "the most important milestone in the European unification
process."
</P>
<P>
He expressed understanding to the reluctance of certain German
people to give up German mark for the still untested euro, and assured
that the euro would be a stable currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
