<HEADLINE> Uganda Bank Deal Completed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The sale of 49 percent shares of
Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB) was completed Wednesday with its
Malaysian buyer paying the remaining six million U.S. Dollars,
''The New Vision'' paper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 11 million U.S. Dollars deal was fixed between Westmont
Land (Asia) and the privatization unit of Uganda on October 27,
1997.
</P>
<P>
H.S. Dalliwall, the Westmont vice president in charge of
international sales, told the newspaper that the bank had
deposited the money on enterprise development project divestiture
account of Citibank, New York.
</P>
<P>
Leonard Muganwa, the project executive director of enterprise
development of Uganda, said the contract will be signed most
likely the next week.
</P>
<P>
Westmont has informed private enterprise reform and
divestiture that its managing team is ready to assume management
immediately, said Dalliwall. Chris Chan, the chief executive, has
been in the country to familiarize with the circumstance and the
bank, and three other senior officers will be in place by the
next week, he added.
</P>
<P>
Westmont delayed to pay UCB for several times due to financial
crisis in Southeast Asia restricting remittance from its
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The sale of the 49 percent share of UCB is one of the steps of
privatization of state enterprises of Uganda. The government
decided to privatize several state enterprises including the
state Airline, Telecommunication Company, Electric Board and
others. Its petroleum company, UPET, has been taken by Shell
Limited Wednesday, but the amount of the deal was not be
revealed.
</P>
<P>
''A deal with a multinational will put us on a strong footing
and pedestal for the future,'' said I. Esmail, the UPET managing
director. 
</P>
</TEXT>
