<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique, S. Africa, Swaziland Discuss Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The interior ministers of
Mozambique, South Africa and Swaziland met in Maputo Wednesday
and discussed issues involved in the Limpopo Development
Initiative bordering the three countries.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Noticias Thursday quoted Mozambican
Interior Minister Almerino Manhenje as saying that the three
countries hope to take concrete measures to implement the
initiative concerning the development in southern Mozambique,
norther South Africa and part of Swaziland, which involves
social, economic and security issues.
</P>
<P>
Ministers of the three countries also discussed issues of
security and immigration involved in the initiative.
</P>
<P>
Manhenje acknowledged that serious problems still exist in the
field of security and immigration among the three states.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of security will be addressed," said Manhenje,
"Only when security is strengthened, can the economic development
in the region be sustainable."
</P>
<P>
"We have discussed such issues as immigration and smuggling
among these countries," and Limpopo Development Initiative must
be implemented so that a framework would be made to put existing
rules into effect and set up new rules, said Manhenje.
</P>
<P>
He noted that issues like livestocks stolen at the
Mozambican-Swazi border would be discussed by special
institutions of the two states.
</P>
<P>
However, Manhenje said, the approach in which the Swazi
government and its police treat the Mozambicans living in
Swaziland should also be discussed.
</P>
<P>
Participants in the discussion disclosed that the three
ministers also exchanged views on the restoration and
establishment of border inspection posts, especially smuggle
monitoring ones, agreeing that the procedures of passing customs
must be standardized and some kind of travelers should be granted
exemption of visas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
