<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Offer Different Views on Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese experts say that a
buyer's market has emerged across the country in terms of major
farm produce and byproducts, while others disagreed at a recent
seminar held by the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
China's leading newspaper, the People's Daily, today quoted
Kong Xiangzhi, deputy dean of the Department of Rural Economy,
China People's University, as saying that the country's grain
output of 500 million tons in 1996 and of slightly lower in 1997
could be regarded as convergent growth-oriented fluctuation, a
turn from the former divergent disorder-based fluctuation.
</P>
<P>
He added that China has maintained a 500-million-ton grain
production capacity, with market supplies of grain, oil, meat,
eggs, vegetables, fruits and aquatic products showing apparent
features of a buyer's market.
</P>
<P>
Experts holding the same views said the central government is
able to balance grain supply and demand dependent on imports and
exports as well as storage, as the country has become a grain
exporter because of increased grain production in recent years.
</P>
<P>
However, other scholars were not so optimistic, saying that
it's too early for that conclusion. Feng Fahai, a research fellow
at the Chinese Academy of Agricultural Sciences, argued that the
lagging agricultural production conditions remain basically
unchanged because there have been no substantial investment
increases from governments.
</P>
<P>
He warned that China's per-capita grain, fruit and other major
farm products are still low in the world, and that falling prices
for farm produce and byproducts in recent years are the result of
the moderately tight macroeconomic policies instead of grain
oversupply.
</P>
<P>
Ai Yunhang, a research fellow with the Policy Research Office
of the Communist Party of China Central Committee, attributed the
drastic fluctuations of grain production to disorderly market
distribution and the sector's inability to adapt to a market
economy. Agricultural restructuring and industrialization will be
the major targets in the future, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Warns of Reversal in Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan told Xinhua today that a "crisis of confidence" exists
between parties in the Middle East, and warned of "danger if the
peace process fails to move forward, and instead slides
dangerously backwards".
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General Annan issued a written statement in response
to Xinhua reporters' questions concerning his recent five-nation
tour of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He said most leaders he spoke with, both Arab and Israeli,
share a "long-term commitment to peace", and stressed that "we
must build on this and give full support to the mediation efforts
of the United States".
</P>
<P>
He expressed gratitude with the "unprecedented level of
cooperation" between the UN Special Commission and Iraq in recent
years. "I urged the Iraqis to make cooperation a long-term
strategic goal so we can reach a point when the Security Council
could considers lifting sanctions".
</P>
<P>
Annan, who concluded his two-day official visit to China and left
for London at noon today. also addressed UN peace-keeping
missions.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he noted, the Security Council recently acted on his
recommendation and approved a new UN peace-keeping mission for the
Central African Republic, and is currently "considering a similar
mission for Sierra Leone".
</P>
<P>
"This represents a revival of interest in UN peace-keeping, and
I am encouraged by related actions," added Annan.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that China, a permanent member of the UN
Security Council, has a "vital role in authorizing peace-keeping
operations".
</P>
<P>
"I welcome further participation by China which already
involved in peace-keeping missions in the Middle East and Africa,"
Annan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
