<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Records 100,000 Maternal Deaths Yearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria records about 100,000
maternal deaths annually despite improvements in health care, the
Health Minister disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deaths occurred from severe bleeding, infections,
pregnancy-induced hypertension, unsafe abortions and
prolonged/obstructed labor.
</P>
<P>
Health Minister Iyorwuese Hager disclosed this while
addressing a press conference in the capital Abuja to commemorate
this year's World Health Day.
</P>
<P>
According to Hager, one in 13 Nigerian women faces a lifetime
risk of death during pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of expectant women experience acute obstetric
problems during pregnancy, childbirth and post portum period,
while 15 percent develop life-threatening complications, he
added.
</P>
<P>
To stem the rising maternal deaths, the government has
undertaken a number of measures, including reducing population
growth rate and specially limiting to four the maximum number of
children per woman.
</P>
<P>
The government also developed a national maternal and child
health policy in 1994, along with a national plan of action to
achieve policy goals.
</P>
<P>
Training of traditional birth attendants and voluntary health
workers has become regular.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging that most of the deaths emanate from preventable
and curable ailments, the minister listed lapses in health
delivery services, lack of public transportation system and good
roads as impediments to safe motherhood.
</P>
<P>
He also canvassed the improvement of socio-economic status of
women and eradication of harmful traditional practices such as
female genital mutilation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
