<HEADLINE> Angola: UNITA Begins to Relocate Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A high-level mission of the
National Union for Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) arrived
in Luanda late Wednesday, beginning to relocate its leadership to
the Capital city.
</P>
<P>
The mission headed by UNITA Vice-President Antonio Dembo
includes Alcides Sakala, Artur Vinama and Franco Marcolino, all
of whom are members of the Political Commission of the opposition
movement. But UNITA President Jonas Savimbi has not come.
</P>
<P>
Head of the UNITA delegation to the Joint Committee for Peace
Process Isaias Samakuva told the press that the high-profile
mission has come to set up new headquarters in Luanda and will
not leave.
</P>
<P>
The mission will work intensively to create all necessary
conditions to enable other leaders including Savimbi to come
here, said Samakuva.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UNITA-controlled Voice of the Black Cockerel
Radio will shut down after its final broadcasting on Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
The only task remaining is the re-establishment of state
authorities in former UNITA's strongholds Bailundo and Andulo, he
said, adding that UNITA and the Angolan government had agreed
that the task will first be carried out in other UNITA-controlled
areas and eventually in Bailundo and Andulo. For this, Dembo
conveyed a letter from Savimbi to Angolan President Eduardo Dos
Santos.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Minister of Territorial Administration Faustino
Muteka showed the Joint Committee for Peace Process around the
downtown six-story office building the Angolan government
prepared for UNITA.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that United Nations spokesman Juan Carlos
Brandt said Wednesday that the move of UNITA high-level mission
was positive.
</P>
<P>
Carlos hoped that this would be the first step of the
relocation process of UNITA leadership. But he also expressed
regret that UNITA had not completed all the tasks stipulated in
the 1994 Lusaka Peace Accord before the deadline on March 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
