<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Leaders Praise Election Committee Subsector Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) praised the ongoing election for an
800-strong Election Committee Thursday, describing it as "fair and
open as well as highly transparent."
</P>
<P>
Voting for the Election Committee subsector elections, the
first step towards the HKSAR's forthcoming first Legislative
Council elections, began on Thursday morning to choose 588 members
of the Election Committee which should elect 10 Legislative
Council members on May 24.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with reporters here after the polling activities
started, Chief Executive of the HKSAR Tung Chee Hwa said "the
election is fair and open" and "good" for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The 800 members of the Election Committee will be representing
views from all cross-section of our community, and they will take
up a very important responsibility to choose 10 members of the
legislature," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the way of the legislative elections both
tallies with the Basic Law and meets the reality in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
After visiting the polling station at the Hong Kong Park Indoor
Game Hall in the morning, Administrative Secretary of the HKSAR
government Anson Chan told reporters that "there would be a
pick-up in the number of people coming forward to vote."
</P>
<P>
"The election is a fair and open and highly transparent
election process," she said, adding: "I very much hope that all
eligible voters will fulfill their duties as citizens and exercise
their right to vote so that we have a credible legislature that is
fully representative of the community."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Chairman of the Electoral Affairs Commission Woo
Kwok-hing inspected a number of polling stations throughout Hong
Kong to see how polling activities for the Election Committee
subsector elections are going.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, more than 50 staff members of the Registration and
Electoral Office of the HKSAR government are manning an election
hotline and a complaints hotline from 7:00 a.m. local time to 11
p.m. to serve voters and candidates.
</P>
<P>
About 140,000 voters, coming from 31 subsectors representing
various trades, professions, labor and social service sectors, and
district-based organizations, can cast their votes at 90 polling
stations from 7:30 a.m. to 10:30 p.m. Thursday to elect their
representatives on the Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
The final results of Thursday's voting are expected to be
announced on early Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
A total of 588 members will be chosen from 963 candidates
through the elections to join others in forming the Election
Committee, which will be made up also of 95 members already
returned from four uncontested subsectors, 77 ex-officio members
and 40 representatives nominated by the religious subsector.
</P>
<P>
Under the Basic Law, the HKSAR's first Legislative Council will
 be made up of 60 members, with 10 members to be returned by the
Election Committee, 20 elected in the geographical constituencies
through direct elections and 30 chosen from the functional
constituencies on May 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
