<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Improve Air Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Beijing will make great efforts
to improve air quality within the next three years, today's
Guangming Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Air-quality reports released since February 28 showed that the
air over the Chinese capital is seriously polluted.
</P>
<P>
"The air quality in the city is not satisfactory," the paper
quoted Yu Xiaoxuan, vice director of the city's environmental
protection bureau, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some worldwide health organizations regard Beijing as one of the
most seriously polluted cities on the globe.
</P>
<P>
Local residents said they are jittery about the air condition
and hope that anti-pollution measures are taken as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Nitrogen oxide in motor vehicle exhaust, sulphur dioxide from
burning of coal, suspending particles in the air, and carbon
monoxide are the major pollutants, the report said.
</P>
<P>
During the last 10 years, the number of motor vehicles in
Beijing has increased from 200,000 to 1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
To reduce air pollution, the city government has forced car
manufacturers to install exhaust purifiers on their products since
the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has also decided to extensively replace coal with
natural gas, which is economical and environmentally friendly.
</P>
<P>
More trees and grass will be planted in the city to reduce air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the city will release daily air-quality reports
beginning from June.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has established eight monitoring stations to test
air quality in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
