<HEADLINE> U.N. Group Inspects China's Border Ports of Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- An investigative group of customs
and port officials, organized by the United Unions Development
Program (UNDP), inspected six Chinese border ports of entry for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
The ports include Huichun and Tumen in Jilin Province,
Dongning and Suifenhe in Heilongjiang Province, Ruili in Yunnan
Province and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
The group consists of 17 senior officials from customs,
frontier and diplomatic departments of China, the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea, Mongolia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the inspection's main purpose was to learn more
about the customs clearance situation of the countries bordering
the Tumen River area, increase contacts and exchanges to speed up
customs clearance and the development of regional trade. 
</P>
