<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Exports Register Marginal Upturn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- India's exports registered a
marginal growth of 1.6 percent in February 1998 following the
negative growth for the last three consecutive months, a leading
newspaper here reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Times of India said the upturn helped to push up the
cumulative export growth during the first 11 months of 1997-98
financial year to 2.63 percent from 2.37 percent during the first
10 months of 1997-98 financial year, which is from April 1, 1997
to March 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Exports in February 1998 were valued at 2694.17 million U.S.
dollars while exports in the same month last year were 2651.68
U.S. dollars, according to latest trade data released Wednesday by
the Ministry of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
During the 11 months from April 1997 to February 1998, exports
were estimated at 30584.86 million U.S. dollars against 29800.31
million U.S. dollars during the corresponding 11 months of the
previous financial year.
</P>
<P>
Imports in February 1998 were valued at 3506.02 million U.S.
dollars, representing a decline of 1.26 percent over the level of
that in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
Imports in the first 11 months of 1997-98 financial year
amounted to 23983.29 million U.S. dollars, 5.49 percent higher
than the level of 35057.09 Million U.S. dollars during the
corresponding period of 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Oil imports were valued at 7084.61 million U.S. dollars,
showing a 19.04 percent decline, while non-oil imports went up by
13.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
India's trade deficit during the first 11 months of the 1997-98
financial year widened to 6389.43 million U.S. dollars from
5256.78 million U.S. dollars in the corresponding period of
1996-97. 
</P>
</TEXT>
