<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge in Tokyo on Weak Business Confidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo Thursday
with the key Nikkei index ending below the 16,000 line for the first
time since January 14, after the Tankan report of the Bank of Japan (BOJ)
underscored a worsening of business confidence.
</P>
<P>
The key Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
on the Tokyo Stock Exchange tumbled 538.76 points, or 3.32 percent
from Wednesday's close to 15,702.90.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, lost 42.17 points, or 3.42 percent to
1,189.36.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section went up to an estimated 700 million
shares from Wednesday's 550 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was Thursday's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Tokyo stocks were sold almost across the board, as the Tankan
survey report, released before the market opened, showed that business
confidence has deteriorated in all indexes -- manufacturers and
nonmanufacturers, big and small, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,328 issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outpaced gainers 1,147 to 83, with 44 remaining unchanged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
