<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea's Foreign Debts Down in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 2 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's foreign debts stood at
150.3 billion U.S. dollars at the end of February, down 900
million from January, the Ministry of Finance and Economy said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, the government's long-term foreign debts,
including bailout loan from the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
rose 1.7 billion while the private sector's
short-term debt fell 2.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
South Korea saw a foreign debt of 150 billion U.S. dollars last
December when the country signed an agreement with the IMF for a
rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars to curb the financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's foreign exchange reserves, which stood at nine
billion U.S. dollars when the crisis occurred last year, steadily
rose to 24 billion U.S. dollar at the end of March thanks to trade
surplus in the past several months and the smooth inflow of funds
from the IMF and other international financial institutions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
