<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Fish in Dishes of Beijing Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Among numerous changes taking
place in the Chinese capital every day, a change in local
residents' food choices reflects a change in urban lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the per capita meat consumption in
1997 by local residents was 39 kilograms (kg) and the amount of
aquatic products was 39.5 kg.
</P>
<P>
The per capita consumption of aquatic products is higher than
last year's world average of 23 kg and the national average of 26
kg, today's Beijing Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Consumption of aquatic products has increased rapidly in the
Chinese capital. During the 1977-1987 period, the per capita
consumption of aquatic products increased from 8 kg to 20 kg.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that more than 30 types of live fish are
available in local markets every day, in addition to more than 130
types of frozen aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
To satisfy the demand of urban Beijing residents, more suburban
farmers have joined the efforts to breed fish. There are 6,666.7
hectares of fish ponds in Beijing's suburbs.
</P>
<P>
The output of aquatic products in China has increased an
average of 12.5 percent yearly during the past decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
