<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawian President Reshuffles Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Malawian President Bakili Muluzi,
under pressure from donors to cut spending, has cut down and
reshuffled his cabinet, Zambia's leading independent newspaper
the Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi has cut three ministries, but created a new portfolio
of privatization, leaving him with 23 ministers and 11 deputies,
said the paper Tuesday which did not give further details.
</P>
<P>
The three ministries abolished are National Heritage, Relief
and Rehabilitation, and Energy and Mining.
</P>
<P>
Two officials who lost their jobs are Minister of Local
Government Chakakala Chaziya and Robson Mukuwira, Minister of
District Administration.
</P>
<P>
Five deputy ministers have also been fired, with one new
Deputy Minister Bob Khamisa appointed to the Ministry of Commerce
and Industry.
</P>
<P>
Cassim Chilumpha, former Justice Minister and
Attorney-General, has moved to finance, taking over from
Vice-President Justin Malewezi, who is now Minister for
Privatization.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank, which is backing Malawi's economic reforms,
has long urged Muluzi to trim his cabinet to cut spending.
</P>
<P>
However, the Malawian president says the reforms have failed
to create economic growth in his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
