<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Optimism Voiced for China's Long-Term Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China's State Information Center
forecasts that China's will enjoy a clear economic upsurge in the
second half of 1998 when considering factors such as capital
sufficiency, labor, technological advancement and system
changes.
</P>
<P>
The center released a report today indicating that the
interaction of the aforementioned factors will constitute the
fundamental driving force behind economic growth, and noted that
existing conditions will be highly beneficial for the nation's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Optimism concerning the long-term prospects for China's
economic development prevail if major problems existing in the
present economic arena are properly solved, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
It notes the fact that China's domestic savings rate has
remained higher than the investment rate in fixed assets during
the 1990s fully demonstrates the nation's solid domestic capital
base and that domestic savings deposits will provide reliable
support for both high investment and economic growth rates.
</P>
<P>
Steadily rising income and consumption demand provides China
with the capability of maintaining a high domestic savings rate
for a relatively long period to come. An increased influx of
foreign capital will greatly enhance the feasibility for China to
achieve a high economic growth rate by increasing investments in
fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
China has abundant labor resources, with an increasing number
of university graduates and students returning from overseas
providing providing a vast reservoir of professionals for
high-tech development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government is paying increasing attention to
investment in human resources, with constant enhancements in the
social status of scientists and technicians. In addition, sharp
increases have been recorded in the number of workers receiving
in-service training. The combined factors have created sufficient
labor resources for economic development.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that scientific and technological advancement
offers vast potential for China's economic development. China has
achieved an average annual GDP growth rate of nearly 10 percent
over the past 10-plus years, with increased investments
representing the driving force behind the economy.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that technological advancements have
contributed some 30 percent to China's economic growth, but note
that the level is far behind levels of developed countries.
</P>
<P>
System reform also represents a significant driving force
behind sustained economic growth, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China not
only effectively ended disputes concerning "ownership", but gave
the green light for private businesses and State-owned enterprises
to further deepen reform. In addition, competition resulting from
diversified forms of ownership will to some extent
increase productivity.
</P>
<P>
In terms of this year's economic prospects, the report noted
the government's objective for an eight percent economic growth
rate can be achieved if the margin of increased investment is
maintained at about 15 percent. It also noted that capital
resources for fixed asset investments should eliminate all worry
about maintaining the margin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
