<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Removes Cess Levy On Rubber Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
removed the cess levy on all rubber exports, the official Daily
News reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Plantation Minister Ratnasiri Wickremanayake was quoted as
saying that the government has taken this measure to provide
immediate relief to rubber small holders and to protect the rubber
industry.
</P>
<P>
The cess levy which was 5.41 Rs (0.09 U.S. dollars) on every
kilogram of rubber exported, will not be charged in future so as
to enable Sri Lankan rubber to compete effectively in the world
market, the Minister, told the paper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The abolition of the cess is expected to provide some measure
of relief to rubber producers by way of an increase in the Colombo
auction price of rubber.
</P>
<P>
About 65 percent of the country's total rubber lands are owned
by small holders. The average unit size in the rubber small holder
sector is around 0.5 per hectare and the majority of the small
holders produce Ribbed Smoked Sheets (RSS) grades 3, 4 and 5.
</P>
<P>
The current average production cost of RSS grades of rubber for
the small holder varies from 40 Rs (0.66 U.S. dollars) to 41 Rs
(0.67 U.S. dollars) a kilogram. However, the current market price
of a RSS grade 4 kilogram is less than its cost of production,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It added that the situation will be reviewed once the RSS 4
graded price of the Rubber Development Department reaches 50 Rs
(0.82 U.S. dollars) a kilogram or after six months from the date
of the abolition of the levy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
