<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Tighten Security After Death of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Israeli police are on
"heightened alert" after the radical Islamic group Hamas
threatened to avenge the death of one of its activists Muhei
Eddine Sharif, the Jerusalem Post daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Police Inspector-General Yehuda Wilk on Wednesday
decided to put the police on alert on Thursday after discussing
security steps with top police officers.
</P>
<P>
Wilk said there already have been plans to take extra security
measures during the Jewish Pessah holidays in mid-April, but due
to Sharif's death the measures will be reenforced.
</P>
<P>
"There will certainly be a heightened alert of the police," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The body of Sharif was found on Sunday after an explosion in
the West Bank city Ramallah. He was suspected of having
masterminded several suicide bombing attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials contended that Sharif was shot to death
by Israeli forces before his body was dumped in a car rigged with
explosives and detonated the blast by remote control in an attempt
to cover up the assassination.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security sources insisted that Israel was not
responsible for the explosion, noting that Sharif was killed
amid a violent rift within the Islamic movement.
</P>
<P>
Hamas unleashed threats on Wednesday to attack Jewish targets
in retaliation for Sharif's death.
</P>
<P>
"As part of our assessment, we take into account the
declarations of the Hamas. In the past they made declarations and
carried them out," the Israeli police chief said.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has carried out more than a dozen suicide bombing attacks
in Israel since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli security troops are bracing against unrest
after the mass funeral of Sharif in Ramallah on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is a situation where there are chances of an attack and we
have to take precautions," said a military official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
