<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Provincial Schools Get Free Access to Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Blessed are those secondary
school students across Thailand who can enjoy free access to the
internet through the so-called schoolnet from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They must thank for the extensive "behind-the-scenes" work
that has enabled free dial-up access from every province in the
country, the Bangkok Post said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This pioneering work, which puts the country ahead of others
in the region, was spearheaded by the National Electronics and
Computer Technology Center (NECTEC).
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Princess Sirindhorn declared the network open
during a private visit to NECTEC.
</P>
<P>
Schoolnet offers internet access and uses the ppp protocol. It
is now accessible free-of-charge by all school members who may
dial a single special number from anywhere in the country. No
long-distance phone charge is involved.
</P>
<P>
According to NECTEC Director, Professor Pairash Thajchayapong,
schoolnet began as a pilot project in 1995, which is "a
substantial component for the survival of Thailand in the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
The network was enabled without any specific national funding,
thanks to other resources and projects and much behind the scenes
work.
</P>
<P>
Resources include the Thai Social/Scientific, Academic and
Research Network, the country's largest league of higher education
institution network, and NECTEC's own network testing laboratory,
and later the "Golden Jubilee Network Project", which was set up
to celebrate the King's 50th anniversary of accession to the
throne in 1996.
</P>
<P>
International companies such as Compaq, Microsoft, Intel also
lent a hand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
