<HEADLINE> Russians Win Pairs in World Figure Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Elina Berezhnaya and
Anton Sikharulidze won the gold of the pair program at the World
Figure Skating Championships in Minneapolis, Minnesota on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Jenni Meno and Todd Sand of the United States bagged the silver
and Germany's Peggy Schwarz and Mirko Muller finished third.
</P>
<P>
Shen Xue and Zhao Hongbo of China recorded in the fourth place,
the best mark for both China and Asia at World Championships or
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Their near perfect performance gained a long-time applause from
more than 13,000 spectators, who greeted the Chinese pair in
standing.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese pair, who were from Northeast China, improved their
positions from the fifth at the Nagano Winter Olympic Games and
tenth at World Figur Skating Championships last year.
</P>
<P>
Their free program performance received a second highest mark
after that for the Russian pair, but slipped away from the medal
podium due to a small fault at the short program Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian pair, who was finished second at the short program
because of Sikharulidze's fall, took over the Chinese and other
rivals for their excellent skating.
</P>
<P>
"It was difficult for us to go out and skate after yesterday's
mistake," said Berezhnaya after their skating on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Americans, feeling pretty great last night with their first
position at the short program, said they were glad for what they
did tonight although they made "a few little mistakes," said
Mero.
</P>
<P>
However, Sand said they were fortunate to get a medal. 
</P>
