<HEADLINE> Bangkok to Set Up First Riverside Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK April 2 (Xinhua) -- For the first time ever, Bangkok
citizens will be able to enjoy their leisure hours along the
famous Chao Phraya river as the metropolitan authorities are
planning to build the first public park next to the river.
</P>
<P>
A nine-rai (1.44 hectares) plot of land around a historical
fort along the river will be developed into a public park, which
will become a new tourist attraction of the city.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post newspaper Thursday quoted Bangkok Governor
Bhichit Rattakul as saying that the waterfront was to be developed
on eight and a half rai (1.36 hectares) of land covering three
plots belonging to two government departments and the Bangkok
Metropolitan Administration (BMA).
</P>
<P>
A concrete riverside corridor measuring 510 meters in length
and three meters wide will also be built along the Chao Phraya
river.
</P>
<P>
Besides these plots, a nearby four-rai (0.64 hectares) plot of
land which houses an old printing house will be turned into a
public park. The building will be torn down.
</P>
<P>
"Bangkokians live close to the Chao Phraya river but they
hardly have a chance to feel and touch the river because most of
the riverside areas are occupied by private individuals," the
governor said.
</P>
<P>
A BMA official said the project will cost about 130 million
baht (3.4 million U.S. dollars). The government would be requested
to upgrade it as a national project.
</P>
<P>
The project is expected to finish before next December.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
