<HEADLINE> Sino-Foreign Cooperation Helps Gold Prospecting in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Cooperating with foreign mining
companies, northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region has
begun prospecting gold reserves in the region's Kirghiz Autonomous
Prefecture of Kizilsu.
</P>
<P>
The prefecture, located on the Pamirs at the juncture of the
Tianshan and Kunlun mountains, is a likely site for gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
Because of its bad climate and inaccessibility, gold reserves
have not been discovered in the past decades.
</P>
<P>
To prospect and develop the prefecture's gold reserves, the
regiona's mining department has signed agreements with Broken Hill
Proprietary (BHP) from Australia, the world's second largest
mining company, and Barrick Resources Corp. from Canada, the
world's third largest.
</P>
<P>
An experimental zone to attract overseas investment for gold
prospecting, the first of its kind in the country, has been
approved for the prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Experts have made on-the-spot investigations in six areas,
including Artux, Akto, Akqi and Wuqia. They expect to discover
gold deposits within the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
