<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Organizing Climb of Tibet's Mount Qomolangma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China will organize a 100-member
team consisting of foreign and domestic tourists to climb Mount
Qomolangma in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wansheng, deputy-director of the Tourism Bureau of the
Tibet Autonomous Region, said here today that the activity will be
supported by the China Mountaineering Association to mark the 40th
anniversary of man's first successful peak climb.
</P>
<P>
A 30-odd-member press delegation will also join the adventure
during which they will clean up rubbish left by previous climbers,
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Before they reach the foot of the mountain, the two teams will
visit the most famous cities, lamaseries, lakes, mountains and
historical sites in Tibet in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
On May 20, they will arrive at the base camp on the mountain,
some 5,200 meters above sea level, and start the expedition.
</P>
<P>
May is the best period for climbing Mount Qomolangma, said
Zhang, adding that his bureau will prepare tents, sleeping bags
and oxygen masks for the climbers.
</P>
<P>
Tourists who have received no training usually can reach more
than 6,000 meters above sea level, he said. The mountain is 8,848
meters above sea level.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that he especially welcome foreigners to take part
in the expedition, which will help them know a true Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Some 350,000 tourists visited Tibet last year, up 7.7 percent
over 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
