<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ill Jaguar Saved in Guangxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- An ill jaguar's life has been
saved by timely treatment at the Zhongshan Zoo in Wuzhou in
southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The six-month-old jaguar was transported to Wuzhou from
Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong Province. It fell
ill two weeks ago, and the situation turned grave after several
days.
</P>
<P>
The animal suffered from dirarrhoea and lost appetite day by
day. The amount of meat it ate daily fell to one kilogram from two
kilograms. It fainted away on March 21, with its body temperatures
dropping below 35 degrees Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Two veterinarians from the Guangzhou Zoo, home of the jaguar,
rushed to the Wuzhou Zoo. After three days of round-clock
treatment and meticulous care, the jaguar has survived the
dangerous phase, and is expected to gradually be restored to full
health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
