<HEADLINE> New Australian Consul-General in Hong Kong Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Female diplomat Susan Boyd will
replace Geoff Walsh as Australia's next consul-general in Hong
Kong, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer announced here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I have today announced the appointment of Susan Boyd as
Australian Consul-General in the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of the People's Republic of China," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
"Boyd has been Australian Ambassador to Vietnam since October
1994," the foreign minister said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Boyd, who is expected to take up her appointment in June 1998,
has served in Bangladesh as high commissioner, and in Lisbon, East
Berlin and the Australian Mission to the United Nations in New
York since joining the Australian foreign ministry in 1970.
</P>
<P>
With a bachelor of arts degree and a diploma of education from
the University of Western Australia, Boyd had three years'
experience as a journalist with the Perth Daily News.
</P>
<P>
Her predecessor Walsh has been consul-general in Hong Kong
since August 1995.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong SAR is a major regional and international
financial, trade, services and media center located in the dynamic
southern part of China where Australia has extensive and important
interests," Downer said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is Australia's eighth largest export market, the 11th
largest trading partner and our fourth largest source of overseas
students, and tourism from Hong Kong to Australia also remains
strong, he said.
</P>
<P>
Over 30,000 Australians live in Hong Kong, the largest
Australian expatriate community in Asia, with more than 350
Australian companies represented there, Downer said.
</P>
<P>
Australia has welcomed the developments in the Hong Kong SAR
since its establishment in July last year, and strongly supports
the continuation of those elements of Hong Kong's way of life that
have underpinned its success: its free economy, free press, the
rule of law, and its evolving democratic institutions, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
