<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aggressive Japanese Banks Burdened with Bad Loans Leave U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese banks, whose aggressive
approach in the United States frightened Americans a decade ago, are
now leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
They paid high prices to get into the U.S., and as they now get
out, they sell at a huge discount.
</P>
<P>
A decade ago, Japanese banks were the buyers. Dai-Ichi Kangyo
paid 1.4 billion U.S. dollars for its stake in CIT, Bank of Tokyo
put up 750 million dollars for California's Union Bank, and Fuji
offered 425 million dollars for Heller Financial, a Chicago-based
commercial finance company.
</P>
<P>
Now they are selling their U.S. financial assets. Burdened with an
estimated 592 billion dollars of bad loans, Japanese banks are eager
to raise money. Although banks such as Tokyo-Mitsubishi and Sanwa are
expected to keep their California subsidiaries, more are leaving.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Sumitomo Bank agreed to sell its California subsidiary
for 546 million U.S. dollars, about one-third the price similar banks
are fetching. It was a surprise because the price being paid to the
company's public shareholders was about 24 percent below the market
price.
</P>
<P>
Tokai Bank also agreed to pay junk-bond yields to raise one billion
dollars in a sale of preferred stock last month.
</P>
<P>
Industrial Bank of Japan and other Japanese banks in recent months
sold almost 10 billion dollars in loans they made to U.S. companies.
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank last year sold a 20 percent stake in its CIT
Group to the public, raising 850 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the transactions would have been impossible in
the 1980s, when a booming Tokyo stock market and a tumbling U.S.
dollar turned Japanese banks into some of the world's biggest
institutional investors and lenders.
</P>
<P>
While many Japanese banks are exiting their U.S. business, U.S.
businesses are eager to edge into Japan, the world's second-largest
market.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by Japan's Big Bang package of economic reforms intended
to deregulate the country's financial markets, U.S. companies, from
financial firms to high-tech providers, hope to find new opportunities
there.
</P>
<P>
U.S. computer companies, software firms and telecome providers also
stand to find new markets amid Tokyo's financial wreckage.
</P>
<P>
U.S. exporters hope the reform as well as 121-billion-dollar worth
of tax cuts and public spending announced last month will kick-start
the Japanese economy. Exports expected to do with in Japan's reform
environment include computer software, computer hardware, and sale
tools such as Website designers, telecom suppliers and telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
Americans also expect buying opportunities as the financial turmoil
in Tokyo has weakened the country's once-strong barriers against
inward investment and foreign takeover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Domestic Car Production Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's car and motorcycle
production in the first two months of this year dropped sharply
compared to the same period last year, the automobile industry
club of the Federation of Thai Industries says.
</P>
<P>
The decline reflects lower purchasing power and higher
production costs due to tax increases and the baht depreciation,
the Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Car production in January and February totalled 16,077 units,
down by 64,781 units, or 80.12 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, motocycle production totaled 89,969 units, down by
119,148 units or 56.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the domestic slump, exports of cars,
motorcycles and parts continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
The value of exported automobile products in January and
February reached 6.096 billion baht (160.4 million U.S. dollars),
recording an increase of 89.1 percent compared to the first two
months of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
