<HEADLINE> Russian Skaters Lead Short Program in World Figure Skating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian skaters led the men's
short program on Wednesday, the second day of the six-day World
Figure Skating Championships held at Mineapolis, Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
Russian Alexei Yagudin, the 1998 European Champion and the
fifth-place at the Winter Olympic Games in Nagano, Japan, finished
first with his countryman Evgeni Plushenko taking the second place.
</P>
<P>
The third place went to America's Michael Weiss, who performed
seventh at the 1998 Winter Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
China's Guo Zhengxin, the best man's skater in Asia who was
placed eighth at the Nagano Olympic Games, moved to the 14th in
the short program, which is not his strong event, because of a
failure in the last triple axel.
</P>
<P>
However, Guo, who played well the whole program, said he felt
confident to perform better in the second half, the free program
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Also, Yagudin said he did not play his best. "For some reason,
it was too hard to skate. My jumps were not straight." But he said
he did his job.
</P>
<P>
The other Russian, Plushenko, said, "This is my first
Worlds. It's like a debut for me. So, I was a bit nervous. I
landed my triple axel on two feet. But overall, I am proud of how
I did." 
</P>
