<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Revenue be Used Efficiently, "Outlook" Weekly Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China should tighten its grip over
fiscal expenditures, making a more reasonable use of Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) revenue, reports Beijing-based weekly
"Outlook".
</P>
<P>
Some government bodies have been found to be too lavish with
the public funds at their disposal. Some use the money to build
unnecessary training and meeting centers and hotels, some of which
were later found to be used as recreational centers, says an
"Outlook" article.
</P>
<P>
Some rashly use the money to take business trips. Some even use
the money to buy personal luxuries such as mobile phones and
limousines.
</P>
<P>
In addition, blind and repeated infrastructure construction by
many government bodies and bloated institutions drains off large
amounts of public funds, it adds.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Ministry of Finance indicate that every
year the state has to spend over 360 billion yuan (43.48 billion
US dollars) to feed people working in governmental institutions
and organizations, a staggering sum that accounts for almost half
of state revenues.
</P>
<P>
Any waste of public funds is appalling, and can only worsen the
shortage and slow down the economic locomotive, the article said.
</P>
<P>
China's current fiscal supply system still reveals strong
vestiges of the old centrally planned economy in which the state
shouldered a heavy fiscal burden of social welfare spending, it reports.
</P>
<P>
The burden of social spending not only puts pressure on the
budget deficit and makes the government vulnerable to political
attack, but almost surely adds inefficiencies to the labor and
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
To change the situation, the article says, the state should cut
back wasteful social expenditures, withdrawing from the role that
should be played by market forces and society.
</P>
<P>
It outlines three measures to change these phenomenon:
</P>
<P>
-- Cut back welfare subsidies to urban residents;
</P>
<P>
-- State money should be spent more on projects embodying
common or long-term interests of the society. Such projects
include science and technology, education, health and a social
security system;
</P>
<P>
-- Reform the system that allows all state-owned enterprises to
always rely on government subsidies to keep running.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
