<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Donor Countries Agree to Help Indonesia's Social Needs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- International donors agreed
here Wednesday to work closely together to help Indonesia overcome
the urgent social consequences of the financial crisis and its
worst drought this century, the World Bank said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of Indonesia, the United States, Australia,
Japan, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Britain, France, Italy,
Belgium, Denmark, Finland, Germany, Sweden, Switzerland and Canada
as well as the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the Asian
Development Bank (ADB), the European Commission, the UN agencies
and other institutions, assessed Indonesia's needs at an all-day
working-level session chaired by Jean-Michel Severino, Vice
President of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The participants reviewed contributions, priorities and policy
initiatives on poverty alleviation and drought relief and
discussed ways of enhancing support for the crisis-ridden
country. It was acknowledged that many activities were underway
with many more to come, necessitating greater consultation and
coordination.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to develop a full coordination
mechanism in Jakarta, capital of the country.
</P>
<P>
The meeting focused on four main areas: the impact of the
three-year-old drought and food security, social services, health
and education, poverty impact, social protection and unemployment,
and protecting Indonesia's physical, human and natural resources
during the crisis period.
</P>
<P>
While donors agreed that the Indonesian government has arranged
adequated food supplies over the short term, the World Bank
estimated that the country may need to import three to four
million tons of rice in coming months depending on the success of
the forthcoming harvest, the overcoming of distribution problems
and the progress of the El Nino effect.
</P>
<P>
The participants also agreed that aside from financial support
for imports and subsidies for rice and soybeans, the key near term
priority for the Indonesian government and the international
community is ensuring that letters of credit for grain imports are
backed adequately and that trader confidence is maintained to
prevent a repeat of the delays in early January and February.
</P>
<P>
To back Indonesia's economic recovery and return to growth, the
World Bank plans to disburse 4.5 billion U.S. dollars over the
next three years, emphasizing a framework for macroeconomic
stability, financial sector reform, competition policy and
regulatory reform, and sustained economic growth. Of the total
pledged, the World Bank will provide two billion dollars to support
financial sector restructuring and long-term structural policy
reform this year.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, the World Bank's lending to Indonesia is nearly 25
billion dollars, with 78 projects currently being implemented with
a 91 percent satisfactory approval rating. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
