<HEADLINE> UN Warns of Food Shortage in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations has warned that
the long drought and monetary crisis is threatening Indonesia's
food security and the rice imports could reach record levels this
year.
</P>
<P>
The warning was made here Wednesday by an 11-member team of
officials from the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the
World Food Program (WFP) which just concluded a three-week study
in the country.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the team said that delayed and
irregular rainfall, reduced use of fertilizer and low quality
seeds could also lead to a reduced rice harvest.
</P>
<P>
It said 7.5 million people living in 15 provinces risked
experiencing food insecurity until early 1999 if the prolonged dry
season lasts much longer.
</P>
<P>
"However, the condition still falls short of a famine," said
the release.
</P>
<P>
The team, however, predicted that the production of most
secondary crops such as soybeans, cassava, maize and sweet
potatoes as well as ground nut will increase and should provide a
limited food security cushion.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the drought, Indonesia is also facing its worst
economic crisis in 30 years. The rupiah (national currency) has
plunged more than 70 percent and this has caused inflation and
unemployment to soar.
</P>
<P>
World Bank Country Director for Indonesia Dennius de Tray said
Tuesday that Indonesia's bill for key imports could be anything
between 1.5 billion and 3 billion U.S. dollars over the next 12
months.
</P>
<P>
The bank warned that Indonesia would have to import at least
four million tons of rice this year to feed its 202.5 million
people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
