<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Create First Securities Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The Ho Chi Minh Securities Exchange,
the first of its kind in Vietnam, will be established later this
year, the English-language newspaper Vietnam News reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the State Securities Commission (SCC) as saying that
this will be the first step toward the country's long awaited
stock market.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government plans to equitise a number of
state-owned enterprises as part of efforts to create a securities
market.
</P>
<P>
As of last month, 28 of the country's 5,790 firms have been
equitised and five of these have been permitted to issue stocks.
</P>
<P>
To increase the attraction of stocks, the SSC has asked the
government to permit equitisation in profitable and fast growing
state industries, including firms in telecommunications, oil and
gas.
</P>
<P>
The first stocks to be traded when the exchange opens will be
those issued by equitised firms and commercial banks, a SSC
official said.
</P>
<P>
To ensure its smooth operation, the SSC is concentrating on
staff training in brokering, consulting and transacting deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
