<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Hits Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has recently recorded its
highest temperature in southern areas for the past 80 years, with
a temperature of 40.6 degrees celsius, the press said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The hot weather is causing a drought, which has adversely
affected agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the meteorology and hydrology department
attributed the prolonged hot spell to the El Nino phenomenon. They
said that it could affect weather conditions until May.
</P>
<P>
In Ho Chi Minh City, the number of children suffering from
respiratory, intestinal and digestive disorders has increased
dramatically. Most children admitted to hospitals are experiencing
respiratory problems, diarrhoea and high fevers because of the
heat.
</P>
<P>
Many factories in the city are fighting the high temperatures
by installing hundreds of fans and ventilators.
</P>
<P>
Residents in the city have been flocking to swimming pools to
escape the heat wave. The cultural labor house swimming pool has
been overcrowded at times with over 3,000 swimmers, nearly double
the pool's average attendance.
</P>
<P>
In the Mekong Delta, the water level in the upper reaches of
many rivers has fallen to its lowest level in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Many families now have to buy water from tanker trucks at high
prices.
</P>
<P>
In the southern coastal provinces, salt water is encroaching
upon arable land. As a result, nearly 40,000 hectares of rice and
other grain crops have been damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
