<HEADLINE> Thailand's Foreign Reserves Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign reserves
increased by 600 million U.S. dollars in the last two weeks of
march, an official of the Bank of Thailand said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official said the increase came as the bank continued to
fulfill its repayment obligations incurred in currency markets
during a futile defense of the baht last year.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand had repaid 400 million U.S. dollars in
swap-market obligations, trimming its net forward position to 15.9
million U.S. dollars, said the official, who asked not to be
named.
</P>
<P>
But he did not provide figures for the present foreign
reserves. Earlier news reports said Thailand's foreign reserves
stood at 26.7 billion U.S. dollars in February.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government had said inflows of foreign capital have
resumed after several months of outflow, contributing to the rise
in foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
The official said the rise in foreign reserves would promote
Thailand's efforts to defuse the currency crisis that broke out in
the country and spread to some other East Asian countries last
year.
</P>
<P>
Although Thailand's foreign reserves rose, its exports dropped
considerably, according newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
Export value fell 7.9 percent in March from the same month a
year ago. The International Monetary Fund estimated that
Thailand's export growth this year will be 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The trade balance is positive only with a larger 45 percent
contraction in imports, which offset the sharp export decline and
that left the balance with an 869-million-dollar surplus in the
month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
