<HEADLINE> Russia, Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan Agree Division of Caspian Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia, Kazakhstan and Azerbaijan
have agreed that the Caspian Sea should be divided from a central
point to the land borders of the five states on its coast, the
Rvestia newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The three countries also agreed that the five states -- Russia,
Kazakhstan, Azerbaijan, Turkmenistan and Iran -- have their own
proprietary rights to the mineral resources, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said Russia and Azerbaijan recently held a
consultation in Baku, the Azerbaijan capital, agreeing a deputy
ministerial meeting should be held as soon as possible to
coordinate their stand on the Caspian Sea's legal status.
</P>
<P>
Since the collapse of the Soviet Union, the countries along the
Caspian Sea have differed greatly on its division. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
