<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mir Crew Starts Six-hour Spacewalk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Two Mir cosmonauts carried out a
six-hour spacewalk Wednesday to reinforce a solar panel damaged in
a space collision last June.
</P>
<P>
Cosmonauts Talgat Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin began Wednesday
evening by opening a lock on a door that refused to budge a month
ago, forcing the cancellation of a spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
A new set of wrenches arrived recently. The two Russians will
attempt to install a splint to reinforce a solar panel that was
damaged in a collision on June 25 between the Mir and a cargo ship.
</P>
<P>
The two cosmonauts are scheduled to make four additional
spacewalks during the first three weeks of April. In addition to
the repair work, they will also try to replace one of the
orientation engines, which keeps the station properly aligned with
the sun.
</P>
<P>
U.S. astronaut Andrew Thomas, also on the station, will stay
aboard the Mir during the spacewalks. In the event of an
emergency, he will withdraw immediately from the station and
return to earth with the two Russians.
</P>
<P>
After a long series of accidents and breakdowns, the
12-year-old Mir has been relatively trouble-free in recent
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
