<HEADLINE> Croatian Foreign Minister Visits Hungary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Croatian Deputy Premier
and Foreign Minister Mate Granic Wednesday encouraged
Croatian-Hungarian refugees fleeing Yugoslav warfare to return
home.
</P>
<P>
Granic made the remark at a news conference following his
meeting with Hungarian Foreign Minister Laszlo Kovacs.
</P>
<P>
There were some 25,000 Croat-Hungarians living in east
Slavonia, now part of Croatia, before war broke out in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meeting Hungarian Prime Minister Horn Gyula, Granic said
Croat-Hungarian refugees would return home as scheduled. The
Croatian government plans to resettle those who return before the
end of the year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Granic and Kovacs also exchanged views on international issues
of common concern in their talks. They agreed their countries
still had good potential for economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian enterprises are preparing to participate in the
Croatian construction, Kovacs said.
</P>
<P>
The two also attended a ribbon-cutting ceremony at the
headquarters of the National Autonomous Government of Hungarian
Croats.
</P>
<P>
Granic said the protection of minority nationalities had played
an important role in Croatian-Hungarian relations. The two
countries' cooperation on this matter could serve as a model for
other East European nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Granic arrived here Tuesday for a two-day visit at the
invitation of Kovacs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
