<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation in Thailand on Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Higher prices in both the food and
non-food sectors pushed inflation in Thailand in March to 9.5
percent compared with 4.5 percent a year earlier and 8.9 percent
in February, according to the Thai Commerce Ministry's Business
Economic Department.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in the first quarter of this year was running at 9.1
percent compared with 4.1 percent in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The department now believes that inflation for the first six
months of this year will stand between 12.5 percent and 13.6
percent. It also forecasts a 12-month figure of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thai consumers will likely see double-digit inflation in April
for the first time in years, Vithun Tulyanond, deputy
director-general of the department, was quoted Thursday by the
Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said food and beverage prices rose 10.5 percent in the first
quarter, while non-food prices were up 8.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vithun said the price increases reflected rising production
</P>
<P>
 costs of consumer products, additional costs of fees, and the
increase in value-added tax to 10 percent from 7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
