<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, IMF Talks on Debt Settlement Close to End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Talks between Indonesian and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) officials on private debt
settlement are close to final, an IMF official said.
</P>
<P>
"The talks have not yet finished but we are satisfied with the
progress. I hope we can conclude it soon," IMF Director for Asia
Pacific Hubert Neiss said here Wednesday night after a meeting
with Indonesian officials.
</P>
<P>
Neiss said the outcome of the talks would be made known to the
public in time by both sides.
</P>
<P>
The two sides began their talks on March 18 on economic reforms
in Indonesia. The talks have focused on corporate debt, bank
restructuring, budget and subsidies, monetary policy and
structural reform.
</P>
<P>
The private debt is believed to be the most difficult issue in
their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
At the end of December last year, Indonesia's foreign debt
totaled to 137.424 billion U.S. dollars, with government debt
worth 63.462 billion dollars and that from the private sector
amounting to 73,926 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government proposed to follow the "Mexican
Model" in settling the private sector debt and the IMF agreed in
principle.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah (national currency) has been under severe
pressure since July last year. It plunged to its lowest level of
17,000 to the U.S. dollar in January, compared to 2,450 in the
pre-crisis period.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah is trading at about 8,300 per dollar now.
</P>
<P>
This has caused most indebted companies to become technically
bankrupt as their foreign debt surpasses their equity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
