<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Troops Take Part in NATO Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine forces will take part in 99
varied activities of the Partnership for Peace of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) this year, including joint
maneuvers in Ukraine, a senior Ukrainian army officer said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nikolai Dzyubak, deputy chief of the General Staff of the
Ukrainian Armed Forces, praised the Partnership for Peace as one
of the most effective mechanisms to boost trust and peace on the
continent, adding that maintaining regular and stable ties between
NATO members and partnership countries will contribute to state
security.
</P>
<P>
Dzyubak said all 16 NATO members and 28 partnership nations,
including Ukraine, will participate in the military alliance's two
maneuvers in Ukraine this year, which are code-named Peace Shield
and Sea Breeze.
</P>
<P>
The Ukraine senior army officer also said 484 Ukrainian
soldiers are participating in United Nations (U.N.) peace-keeping
operations this year, and the U.N. Secretariat has already
earmarked 68 million U.S. dollars for the Ukrainian army.
</P>
<P>
The Partnership for Peace was created in 1994 to increase
military cooperation between the NATO members and former Warsaw
Pact countries.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine also signed a partnership charter with NATO last July,
which proposed frequent political exchanges and increased military
cooperation. 
</P>
