<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Clean-up Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Garbage like plastic-foam food
containers and bottles are a common sight on the waters of the
Yangtze River. But they are expected to disappear soon because of
a state regulation implemented to keep the country's longest river
from solid-waste contamination.
</P>
<P>
The regulation -- issued jointly by the Ministry of
Communication, Ministry of Construction and the National
Environmental Protection Agency -- became effective in March and
prohibits vessels on the Yangtze from dumping garbage into the
river.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also calls for a halt to dumping household
garbage and industrial waste along the banks of the river.
</P>
<P>
the Yangtze river used to be polluted with 30,000 tons of
refuse dumped by ships each year, in addition to more than 360
million tons of liquid containing fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
China has already taken steps to protect the Yangtze. One
measure called for barriers around the ports and harbors to block
the spread of fuel oil from wrecked ships.
</P>
<P>
A fleet of large ships for collecting waterborne refuse has
been patroling the river. These ships are also equipped with
wastewater treatment facilities.
</P>
<P>
A group of mobile pollution-monitoring stations have been built
and will become operational before June to help environmental
protection authorities keep a close watch on the river's water
quality.
</P>
<P>
Growing importance has been given to increasing awareness of
the public on environmental protection. Many ships have special
personnel to publicize environmental protection laws and
regulations, and they are authorized to stop crew members and
passengers from dumping refuse into the water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
