<HEADLINE> Canada Offers Financial aid to Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada has offered to provide
Indonesia with financial aid totaling 1.6 trillion rupiah (about
200 million U.S. dollars) to help overcome the economic crisis and
natural disasters in the country, a senior Indonesian official
said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian aid outside the IMF (International Monetary Fund)
package would be a pure grant without any special conditions
attached and could be disbursed any time, Finance Minister Fuad
Bawazier said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The assistance could be used to finance small business
development programs, forest fire fighting, purchase of medical
supplies and wheat imports, said Bawazier after signing an
agreement on the avoidance of double taxation with Canadian State
Secretary of International financial Institute Jim Peterson,
official Antara News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Bawazier said the Canadian government had also offered
technical assistance to Indonesia in the financial sector
including insurance, pension funds and other economic
restructuring efforts.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has been badly hit by the monetary crisis since July
last year and the rupiah has depreciated by more than 70 percent
against the U.S. dollar. As a result of the crisis, the country is
now faced with spiralling inflation, growing unemployment and
other serious economic and social problems.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia signed an agreement with the IMF at the end of
October last year in exchange for a bailout package of more than
40 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Peterson, who arrived here on March 30 for a three-day visit,
said Wednesday that as a member of the IMF, Canada supports
Indonesia in its efforts to implement the reforms it has promised
to the IMF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
