<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Scraps Border Controls With France, Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Italy ended border controls with
France and Austria on midnight Tuesday in an expansion of a
European Union (EU) open-border pact.
</P>
<P>
Under the Schengen Accord, border controls between seven EU
states -- Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, the Netherlands,
Portugal and Spain -- were eliminated in March 1995. Italy and
Austria were the latest EU countries to become full members of the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Grand ceremonies were held Wednesday morning at Ventimiglia on
the Italian-French border and Brennero on the Italian-Austrian
border to mark the event.
</P>
<P>
Italian Interior Minister Giorgio Napolitano said at Brennero
that the elimination of border controls would further mutual
understanding and cooperation between member states and benefit
Europe.
</P>
<P>
He added that police in each country would tighten their
exterior borders to guard against illegal immigration and crime
from non-EU countries.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen Accord was signed in Luxembourg in 1985 to realize
free movement and promote free trade within the EU. The accord
took effect in 1995 but so far only nine members of the 15 EU
nations have implemented it.
</P>
<P>
Italy partially lifted border controls at some of its main
airports last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second World Telecommunication Conference Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, Malta, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The second world
telecommunication development conference, attended by more than
1,600 delegates from 151 countries, ended here Wednesday with the
adoption of the Valletta Declaration and the Valletta Action Plan.
</P>
<P>
The most important decision made at the 12-day conference is to
set up two special groups to speed up the development of worldwide
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The research group for decision-making will work out
macro-policies that will include financing development and
coordinating ties between the International Telecommunication
Union (ITU) and the telecommunication organization in every
country.
</P>
<P>
Another research group for technology support will study the
overall plan for the development of a worldwide telecommunication
net, the renewal of telecommunication equipment, and the exchange
of new technologies between the ITU and all countries.
</P>
<P>
During the ITU-sponsored conference, the participants presented
schemes for enhancing the development of telecommunications in
rural areas, establishing a fair, just and open mechanism of
competition, training personnel, absorbing private funds and the
investment of world financing organizations. The delegates also
reached consensus on reforming the ITU.
</P>
<P>
Formally founded in 1932, the ITU now has 188 member
nations. In 1947, the ITU became a special branch of the United
Nations. It held its first world telecommunication development
conference in Buenos Aires, Argentina, in March 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
