<HEADLINE> South China Coastal Province Promoting Marine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province in south
China is taking advantage of its proximity to the sea to develop a
marine economy and aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
It reported 85 billion yuan in marine industrial output last
year, one-third of the national total, including 5.15 million tons
of aquatic products valued at more than 40 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong has set up marine economic development bases in such
coastal cities as Shenzhen, Shantou, Zhanjiang, Chaozhou and
Huizhou. It leads the country in breeding prawns, pearls, abalone
and oysters.
</P>
<P>
The province has also increased efforts to promote deep-sea
fishing, using 105 fishing boats and catching 85,000 tons of
aquatic products annually valued at 50 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition, it began cooperation with international
organizations. For example, the United Nations Development Program
provided 330,000 U.S. dollars to set up a resources sustainable
utilization pilot zone on Hailing Island of Yangjiang city.
</P>
