<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Expects Bumper Harvest of Peanuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Argentina's peanut harvest
and exports will grow significantly in 1997-1998 because of
increased cultivation and favorable weather, authorities said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release by the Ministry of Agriculture,
Cattle, Fishing and Food, the country's peanut harvest will reach
776,000 tons, up 177 percent over last year, while peanut exports
will be over 450,000 tons, making Argentina the world's largest
exporter of peanuts this year.
</P>
<P>
The United States and China, major peanut exporters last year,
have suffered reductions in their peanut harvests.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that peanut growing areas in Argentina have
been expanded from 329,000 to 407,000 hectares. The production per
hectare is expected to rise to 1,700 kilograms from 940 kilograms
because of more rain.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Europe (the Netherlands in particular)
are the most important markets for Argentina's peanuts, said the
press release.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Split Over Entry to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda
Mikhailova said Tuesday that her country would qualify for entry
to the European Union (EU) by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailova was speaking after a round of shuttle diplomacy to
promote EU membership for Bulgaria. She also attended a meeting in
Brussels during her visit on the expansion of the EU.
</P>
<P>
She said that Bulgaria's entry depended more on its domestic
reform process than on its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to her optimistic statement, however, the Economic
Institute of Bulgaria's Science Academy argued Bulgaria could only
qualify for membership after 2030.
</P>
<P>
A report by the institute said that based on the country's
gross domestic product alone, it will not be able to reach the EU
standards for at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria officially applied for EU membership in December
1995. But, because of a sluggish economy, it is believed to be far
from qualification standards for entry to the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
