<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Province Cracks Down on Chimneys Pouring out Black Smoke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Hebei Province in north China
plans to eliminate industrial chimneys pouring out black smoke by
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Chimneys churning out black smoke are major pollution sources
in urban areas. According to a survey, the province has more than
60,000 industrial chimneys which were mainly erected for boilers.
</P>
<P>
Since 1996 the province has injected a large amount of funds
into renovating urban heating systems to cut the number of
chimneys. Chengde, a tourist city, introduced foreign funds to
renovate its urban heating system, taking the lead in eliminating
all chimneys pouring out black smoke.
</P>
<P>
The provincial city of Shijiazhuang has renovated more than
8,000 coal-burning facilities, demolished 134 boilers, pulled down
117 chimneys, and equipped 96 percent of the remaining ones to
filter out the pollution.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government also publicized media telephone
numbers to encourage people to monitor the process.
</P>
<P>
After a two-year effort, 49,000 chimneys among the province's
60,000 have been examined and the province has decided to make 95
percent of the chimneys in urban and tourist areas meet state
discharge standards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
