<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts Measures to Ensure Safe Shellfish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China will adopt effective
measures to ensure safe shellfish on market, said today's China
Daily.
</P>
<P>
Shellfish raising areas will be classified in three levels
according to their water environment quality and the standard of
hygiene of the shellfish.
</P>
<P>
Shellfish raised or fished in first-level areas can be sent
directly to the market and that in the second-level should be
purified before being put on the market.
</P>
<P>
The third-level areas, where water and shellfish are heavily
polluted, will not reach the State standard even after treatment
of the shellfish.
</P>
<P>
These areas which had been polluted and not improved for long
periods of time will be closed to raising or fishing of shellfish.
</P>
<P>
Fishing of shellfish from these areas which cause poisoning
will be treated as criminal violation.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also ruled that people who raise shellfish
should hold licences.
</P>
<P>
China is a big shellfish producer. Shellfish production reached
8.9 million tons in 1996, accounting for 27 percent of the
country's total aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
Delicious as seafood, shellfish is prone to pollution as its
habitats can be easily penetrated by chemical materials and
viruses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
