<HEADLINE> Shenyang Introduces Minimum Cost of Living System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Shenyang, capital of northeast
China's Liaoning Province, has introduced a social security system
to provide minimum cost of living allowances for urban residents.
</P>
<P>
Qualified residents living in five urban districts will receive
monthly subsidies of 150 yuan each, with the figure for people
living in suburban areas standing at 130 yuan, and residents in
the city's two counties receiving 120 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 local Shenyang residents are receiving minimum cost
of living allowances.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang, the largest city in northeast China, is home to over
6.7 million people. Some 400,000 redundant workers, or 35 percent
of the province's total population, have lost their jobs during
the course of economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The has established retirement pension and unemployment
insurance systems in recent years to assist people burdened with
financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The city's minimum cost of living system was implemented as
part of a national program. The State Council plans to expand the
system to all urban districts prior to the end of 1999. The
program will represent a major step towards gearing the
traditional social security system to the socialist market
economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
