<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's County Makes a Name by Growing Vegetables </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Vegetable-marketing agents from
across the country are increasingly traveling to Jingyang County
of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The largest vegetable producer and distribution center in
northwest China, Jingyang grows vegetables on 10,000 hectares,
including greenhouses. Last year, it produced 500 million
kilograms of vegetables, earning local farmers an annual per
capita income of 700 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The county had only several hundred hectares of vegetables
before 1992. Jiao Zhixue, a farmer turned entrepreneur, began the
effort by spending 100,000 yuan in one year to set up 17
greenhouses in Yunyang Township.
</P>
<P>
The next year, his company raised 15 million yuan to build
another 1,522 greenhouses in 40 villages, with farmers taking care
of vegetable production and sales by contracts.
</P>
<P>
The company formed a vegetable-growing technique association
with experts providing consultation services, and used 300,000
yuan to buy insurance policies for farmers to grow vegetables in
greenhouses. In addition, it also financed a vegetable wholesale
market in the township.
</P>
<P>
Growers tasted the sweet profits of greenhouse-farming and
intensified their efforts when they collected 120,000 yuan of
earnings per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The 10-hectare vegetable market does 800,000 kilograms of
vegetable business daily, or two million kilograms during busy
seasons. Now, 1,500 vehicles from the county are heading for all
parts of the country, carrying vegetables. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Increases Efforts to Protect Scenic Spots </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- China is making a new effort to
bring the construction of scenic spots nearer to international
practices, according to an official of the Ministry of
Construction.
</P>
<P>
"A law concerning preservation and construction of scenic spots
will be put into effect in a few years, aimed to establish a state
park system in the long run," said Cao Nanyan, head of the
ministry's scenic spots section.
</P>
<P>
China now has 119 state-level scenic spots and historical sites
covering 96,000 square kilometers, accounting for one percent of
the total area.
</P>
<P>
In recent years the country has been making efforts to protect
and build natural and man-made scenic spots and historical
sites. By the end of last year there were 512 scenic spots and
historical sites of different levels, the official said.
</P>
<P>
China has 19 scenic spots and historical sites such as the
Great Wall and the Forbidden City listed as United Nations
heritage sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
