<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier on Asian Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
Wednesday reaffirmed China's determination to provide assistance
within its capacity to some Asian countries and pledged not to
devaluate China's currency.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a reception hosted by China-Britain Trade Group in
central London, Premier Zhu said the Chinese people were
determined to share weal and woe with the Asian friends in such
difficult times.
</P>
<P>
He said although China's economic strength is still very
modest, the Chinese government has provided assistance to these
affected Asian economies within its capacity and made some
concrete contributions to the International Monetary Fund's
bail-out package.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese premier also made it clear that China
will not devaluate its currency because it was against traditional
Chinese values and the Chinese government did not wish to make the
financial crisis develop from bad to worse.
</P>
<P>
"The Asian financial crisis is a bad thing, but if we could sum
up the experience and learn these historical lessons, it could be
turned into a good thing," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu, who arrived in London on Tuesday for an official visit to
Britain, noted that "the financial crisis in Asia has not been
over yet, but the worst has already passed."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out he was confident that the economies of the Asian
countries will be able to recover in a fairly short period of time
and such an economic restructuring would certainly be helpful to
these countries.
</P>
<P>
Although China's commitment not to devaluate its currency has
created some difficulties to the Chinese economy, the Chinese
government was prepared to shoulder its responsibility and make
its sacrifice, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
While briefing China's efforts to reform its state enterprises,
Zhu said the Chinese government is resolving various problems of
its state enterprises with methods of Chinese style and such
reforms can be completed within three years.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu, who promised that China's reform policy remains
unchanged, invited British businessmen to invest in China and take
part in market competition there.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese premier's 45-minute speech received a warm welcome
by some 800 British businessmen and people from other sectors of
society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
