<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Stresses Investments in Fixed Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 2 (Xinhua) -- Guangdong Province, one of
China's economic powerhouses, plans to rely on increased
investments to maintain its leading role in the nation's reform
and opening-up efforts, and simultaneously boost economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Plans call for the province to increase its GDP from the 1985
level of 544 billion yuan to 916.7 billion yuan by the end of the
century. The province will also inject 1.24 trillion yuan into
fixed asset investments between 1996-2000.
</P>
<P>
Government sources indicate that 80 key projects related to the
effort will involve total investments of 353.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Consumption, foreign trade and investment represent the three
major factors driving the province's economic growth. Related
officials note that investments are high on the agenda due to
difficulties involved in achieving significant increases in
consumption and foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong's fixed asset investments for the period between
1991-1995 stood at 759.1 billion yuan, with an average annual
increase of 51 percent, yielding major improvements in local
infrastructure and the development of new economic growth areas.
</P>
<P>
The province also plans to use overseas capital totalling 63.7
billion yuan during the 1996-2000 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
