<HEADLINE> IMF Provides Emergency Post-Conflict Credit for Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) approved Wednesday a credit of 10 million U.S. dollars
equivalent as the second emergency post-conflict credit assistance
for Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
The credit will be used to support the Tajikistan government's
economic program for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The first credit, also about 10 million dollars was approved on
December 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1998 economic program, real GDP growth is expected to
reach 4 to 5 percent this year as against preliminary rates of
about 2 percent in 1997, and about -4 percent in 1996, inflation
is targeted to drop to about 18 percent during 1998, from about
164 percent last year and gross international reserves are
programmed to pick up to 1.4 months of imports by the end of 1998,
from 0.7 months of imports at the end of last year, and 0.3 months
of imports by 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan joined the IMF in April 1993. Its quota is about 80
million dollars and its outstanding use of IMF financing currently
totals about 30 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
