<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees 20 Percent Growth in M&AMP;A in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 1 (Xinhua) -- More than 236 billion U.S.
dollars in merger and acquisition (M&AMP;A) activity from over 2,300
deals were announced in the first quarter of 1998, representing a
20 percent growth in deal value over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release from Securities Data Company on
Wednesday, the present quarter marks the twelfth straight quarter
where domestic M&AMP;A volume exceeded 100 billion dollars and the
third quarter in a row where announced transaction volume has
cracked the 200 billion dollar mark.
</P>
<P>
The telecommunications sector was the leading industry
targeted for takeovers during the first three months of 1998 in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
More than 36 billion dollars or about 15 percent of total
domestic M&AMP;A volume in deals from 56 transactions were announced.
Topping the deals was AT&AMP;T's proposed 11.2 billion dollar
acquisition of Teleport.
</P>
<P>
Sanitary services ranked the second leading sector with over 20
billion dollars in deal volume, and the investment &AMP; commodity
firms, dealers and exchanges group came third with 13.6 billion
dollars from 67 deals.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch was the leading U.S. financial advisor to
complete worldwide M&AMP;A assignments in the first quarter when it
advised on 57 deals with a total value of over 81.00 billion
dollars, the Securities Data Company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
