<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Herbal Medicine Used To Treat Drug Addiction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, April 2 (Xinhua) -- A treatment for drug addiction
made from traditional Chinese herbal medicines has been developed
in southwest China's Guizhou Province.
</P>
<P>
The new medicine, for external use only, was developed by Dai
Qile, a doctor of the Miao nationality, who is an expert in
treating cancer and alimentary canal diseases.
</P>
<P>
Dai has discovered that some traditional Chinese herbal
medicines can decompose the toxicity of drugs such as heroin,
morphine, cocaine and hemp.
</P>
<P>
According to Dai, drug addicts just need to put the pills on
their navel. There is no pain or side-effects, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dai explained that, according to traditional Chinese medicine
and that of the Miao nationality, the navel is connected with
vital organs of the human body, and the effective elements of the
medicine can enter the body through the belly button.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that what is different from commonly used anti-drug
medicine is that the new treatment helps eliminate poison inside
the human body through the principle of neutralizing acid and
alkali and adjusting the functions of the alimentary canal.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Guizhou provincial health bureau said that all
indexes of the medicine are up to the standards set by the state
and the medicine is effective in easing toxicity caused by
morphine-related drugs.
</P>
<P>
Tests on animals also show that the medicine can ease drug
addiction caused by heroin with no new medical addiction.
</P>
<P>
Information coming from hospitals and anti-drug centers in the
United States, Thailand, Malaysia and Hong Kong shows that the
medicine is more effective in reducing drug addiction than
commonly used anti-drug medicine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Arms Embargo Resolution Denounced by Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 1 (Xinhua)-- Yugoslavia has denounced a
new U.N. Security Council resolution on arms embargo against it,
saying that supporters of the embargo were trying to break up the
country by encouraging separatists in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, adopted 14-0 Tuesday with China abstaining in
the 15-member Council, was drafted by France, Germany, Italy,
Japan, Portugal, Sweden, Britain and the United States. It was
designed to pressure Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic into
concessions aimed at "substantial autonomy" for the majority
Albanian population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after the vote, Yugoslavia's Ambassador Vladislav
Jovanovic rejected any involvement by the Council in what he said
were purely internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
In an apparent reference to the United States and Britain,
Jovanovic accused "some permanent members of the Security Council"
of encouraging Albanians who want to secede from Serbia, which
along with Montenegro forms the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
"That policy will bring no good to their own countries, to
Europe, to the world," the Ambassador pointed out. "On the
contrary, it is counterproductive and dangerous to the legal
system of international relations."
</P>
<P>
He said that the goal of the Kosovo Albanians "is the secession
of this certain land from Serbia."
</P>
<P>
"Serbia cannot and will not allow it to happen under any
conditions," Jovanovic stressed.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is regarded by Serbs as the cradle of their nation,
church and culture.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council resolution requires all states, "for the
purpose of fostering peace and stability in Kosovo," to prevent
the sale or supply to Yugoslavia of arms and all types of related
material.
</P>
<P>
The embargo will be monitored by a sanctions committee made up
of all 15 Council members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
