<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 2 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Senator Brian Harradine's declaration on
Wednesday that he would oppose a key component of the federal
government's bill on native titles, or aboriginal rights to claim
land in Australia, laid the foundations for Prime Minister John
Howard to call an early election on the issue of race.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian High Court, the nation's highest law body, has
asserted its power to strike down laws passed by the federal
parliament which may disadvantage a particular race, but has
failed to clarify whether the government's Wik bill, or the bill
on native titles, is constitutional.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Hudson Conway, the senior company in Lloyd Williams'
embattled 1.3 billion U.S. dollar casino empire, Wednesday
foreshadowed a shake-up that would separate it from the empire and
probably from Williams.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan marked the first day of its Big Bang financial reforms
with more economic gloom, as its battered banking system revealed
a record 80 billion U.S. dollars in bad loan losses and a huge
property financier suddenly collapsed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
