<HEADLINE> U.S. to Assess Israeli Offer of Third Pullback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States is assessing
some progress in the Middle East peace process as a result of
Israel's offer of a third pullback on the West Bank, and pondering
how to capitalize on the unexpected gesture for a possible break
of the impasse in the Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations, the
State Department said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, we are going to assess whether any of the modest
progress that Ambassador (Dennis) Ross detected is something we
should try to build on," State Department spokesman James Rubin
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Secretary (of State Madeleine) Albright will be consulting
with the president and other senior officials about that right
away," he said.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources have disclosed that Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu told U.S. special envoy Ross at the end of his
four-day round of shuttle diplomacy that the Israeli government
was willing to discuss with the Palestinians on a third pullback
on the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's offer to Ross prompted Albright to tell reporters
that "some progress" had been made for Ross's mediation in the
region.
</P>
<P>
But Albright also said the progress was not "nearly enough" to
end the deadlock, while Rubin said that "the peace process is
not on track, and the gaps have not been bridged." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
