<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar Foreign Minister Sees Iran Shift on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Qatar's Foreign Minister Sheikh
Hamad bin Jasim al-Thani said Wednesday that he saw a changing
attitude of the Iranian government toward the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"I think we can see some changes," he told reporters after
talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Thani said the changes came as "the Iranians said that the
peace process is belonging to the people of Palestine and the
neighborhood with Israel, and if they accept something, it's their
own fate."
</P>
<P>
"I think this is a positive answer from the Iranians and I hope
this will be in practice their policy for the peace process," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Thani said Qatar enjoyed good relations with Iran and wanted to
see U.S.-Iranian relations improve. But, in reply to a question,
he denied that he had brought any message from Iran to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Earlier before talks with Qatar's foreign minister, Albright
said she was pleased by the warm welcome Iranians gave to an
American wrestling team a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
But she was cautious to say anything about policy changes from
Iran, reiterating that the United States would see actions, not
just listen to words, from the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
"We have spoken about the importance of actions as well as
words," she said.
</P>
<P>
In evaluating the Iranian government, Albright said, it is
"only prudent and responsible" for the United States to look for
changes in Iran's policies on terrorism, the Middle East and
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
