<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Owes U.N. 1.6 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States owes the
United Nations 1.6 billion U.S. dollars for past and current
membership dues as of March 15, according to the latest figures
released by the U.N. Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In its April 1998 Update of the U.N. Financial Crisis at a
Glance, the U.N. said U.S. back dues to the U.N. accounted for
over half of member states' total dues of 2.97 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The debt by the U.S. includes 671 million dollars for the
regular budget and 958 million dollars for peace-keeping.
</P>
<P>
Non-payment of dues by members continues to create a bleak
financial picture for the U.N. So far only 46 of 185 member states
have paid in full their assessments.
</P>
<P>
Total dues consist of 1.7 billion dollars for peace-keeping, 1.2
billion dollars for the regular budget and 72 million dollars for
international tribunals.
</P>
<P>
"Our cash position is weak and getting weaker and our ability
to cross-borrow (from peace-keeping funds) is drying up," said
Joseph E. Connor, U.N. under-secretary-general for administration
and management.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. owed some 70 member states a total of 884 million
dollars for troops and equipment as the U.N. was unable to
reimburse them.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has a zero-growth budget of 2.5 billion dollars for
1998-99 -- 1.25 billion dollars a year, down 100 million dollars
from 1994-95. Carrying out his reform program, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan has cut about 1,000 posts.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. and other countries pushed hard for these cuts, but
have not paid their share of the austerity budget they approved,"
the U.N. said in the Update published by its Department of Public
Information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
