<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Reforms on Track: Wolfensohn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia's reforms remained on
track despite the recent political shakeup and its economy should
grow between 1 and 2 percent in 1998, World Bank President James
Wolfensohn said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn made the remarks at a U.S.-Russia Business Council
forum in Washington, which was also attended by several senior
U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
"(Yeltsin) has not departed from his course," Wolfensohn said.
"I think the way we have to read this recent change is that we are
bringing in a group of younger technocrats who are going to get
the job done."
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, the approach we are taking at the bank is to take
that at face value and move forward with it," he added.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said Russia's economy would be stronger but for the
economic crisis gripping Asia, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, senior U.S. officials praised Yeltsin's progress on
reforms.
</P>
<P>
"There have been important steps in the right direction in
recent months, in efforts to make budgeting more transparent, to
achieve much higher rates of tax collection and to advance the
enactment of a new tax code," said Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, Russia has weathered the recent storms well," said
Summers. He noted that the Russian authorities "have raised
interest rates not once but twice when that was necessary."
</P>
<P>
But Summers said Russia must step up its law enforcement to put
to rest fears of "gangster capitalism" and create the conditions
in which a market economy can thrive.
</P>
<P>
Russia needs to concentrate on collecting taxes, developing an
effective financial system and entrenching the rule of law,
Summers said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Undersecretary of Commerce for International Trade David
Aaron said he thought the Russian economy was showing "greater
resilience than ever."
</P>
<P>
But he said Russia was not ready to join the World Trade
Organization and expressed disappointment with Moscow's latest
offer to enter the Geneva-based global trading body.
</P>
<P>
"It is a good step forward," Aaron told the business council.
"But it falls significantly short of the mark for what would be
necessary to actually enter the WTO."
</P>
<P>
The latest offer by Moscow left open a number of market access
issues, Aaron said. Tariffs were too high in many cases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been negotiating WTO entry for four years, but
Western diplomats say it must take significant steps to reform its
slow customs procedures, open its markets and cut import duties.
</P>
<P>
"Russia must learn the lessons of the Asia crisis. An
important reason for Asia's difficulties has been the closed
nature of many Asian markets," said Aaron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
