<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Stresses Importance of Peacekeeping in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAKAR, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States President Bill
Clinton Wednesday stressed in Senegal the importance of developing
the peacekeeping capability of Africa, so that genocide like the
one in Rwanda will not happen again.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to a military base in Thies some 70 kilometers
east of Dakar, Clinton said: "We should find the means to prevent
such horrors from happening again."
</P>
<P>
Some 30 American instructors are training 400 Senegalese
soldiers for peacekeeping mission in the military base under the
U.S.-sponsored "African Crisis Reaction Initiative (ACRI),"
which is aimed at helping African countries build a peacekeeping
force of their own.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, Malawi, Mali, Ghana and Ethiopia are also joining the
ACRI.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that the goal of the United States is not to
"dominate the questions of security" in Africa, but to cooperate
with the United Nations, the Organization of African Unity,
France, Britain "to reinforce means to preserve peace" on the
black continent.
</P>
<P>
Clinton arrived here Tuesday evening on the last leg of his
six-nation African tour.
</P>
<P>
He will visit the well-known Goree Island off Dakar on
Thursday, which has become a symbol of black slave trade and
served for three centuries as a base for European slave traders to
sell Africans to America.
</P>
<P>
The most famous construction on the island is "the House of
Slaves," which was built in an elegant European colonial style in
the 18th century to jail like "cattles" slaves from across
Africa, before they were sent off on a "trip without return."
</P>
<P>
U.S. first lady Hillary Clinton and her daughter Chelsea
visited the island last year when they visited Senegal. They were
greatly saddened by what they saw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
