<HEADLINE> U.S. Greets Kocharyan as New President in Armenia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- The United States congratulated
Wednesday Robert Kocharyan on his election as president of Armenia
and wished him well in forming a new government.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin also expressed his hope
that Kocharyan would further implement economic and political
reforms and reach a political resolution to the disputed region of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
</P>
<P>
The Armenian Central Elections Commission Wednesday declared
Kocharyan, Armenia's prime minister and acting president, the
winner of the former Soviet republic's presidential runoff
election Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said Washington concurred with the conclusions of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), which
found that while in some areas the election fell short of OSCE
standards, this did not affect the outcome of the vote.
</P>
<P>
"We endorse the conclusions of the OSCE preliminary report
issued by (U.S.) Ambassador Sam Brown on April 1," Rubin said in
a written statement.
</P>
<P>
He urged the new Armenian government to take "immediate and
decisive steps" to eliminate the electoral violations and
irregularities which did occur.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the Armenian authorities to investigate thoroughly
these reported abuses and take appropriate legal action against
those responsible," Rubin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
