<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Bill Demands Safe Gun Storage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- Prompted by last week's
schoolyard slayings in Jonesboro, Arkansas of the United States, a
Senate bill proposed Wednesday would punish adults if children use
their guns to commit a crime.
</P>
<P>
The bipartisan bill, introduced by Senators John Chafee, a
Republican, and his Democratic colleague Richard Durbin, would
require adults to install safety locks on their firearms or lock
them away altogether. Those who do not would face penalties of up
to a year in prison and fines of up to 10,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Durbin said, "It's a sad fact of life that some Americans are
more concerned about locking up their silverware than their guns.
Those who own guns must accept the responsibility of storing and
using them safely."
</P>
<P>
Fifteen states already have similar Child Access Prevention
laws on the books. But the House shot down a similar proposal. The
senators hope the recent tragedy will give their effort new
momentum.
</P>
<P>
Among the gun control advocates who joined the senators at
Wednesday's press conference was former White House press
secretary James Brady, who was shot and critically injured during
an assassination attempt on former President Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
Brady called the number of firearm deaths and injuries to
American kids an "abomination."
</P>
<P>
An estimated 14 children a day are killed in gun-related
homicides, suicides or accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980402.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Emphasizes Ties With Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 1 (Xinhua) -- China believes Indonesia would
overcome its current difficulties under the leadership of
President Suharto, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made this remark when meeting with Indonesian Vice
President Bacharuddin Habibie, who is also in London to attend the
Second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM II).
</P>
<P>
China attaches great importance to Sino-Indonesian relations,
said Premier Zhu.
</P>
<P>
China sincerely sympathizes with Indonesia, which is facing
some difficulties in the current financial crisis. China has
already provided Indonesia with capital and gratuitous material
assistance through the International Monetary Fund, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie expressed sincere gratitude to China for the capital
assistance and material aid.
</P>
<P>
While implementing economic structural adjustments, Indonesia
hopes to strengthen cooperation with China in all fields, Habibie
said.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu also met former British prime ministers Edward
Heath and Mrs. Margaret Thatcher and briefed them on the situation
in China.
</P>
<P>
He hopes that they would make efforts toward the further
improvement of Sino-British relations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu attended a formal welcome lunch party hosted by Lord Derry
Irvine, Lord High Chancellor of the Upper House of Britain, on
the same day.
</P>
<P>
Zhu visited the Bank of England Wednesday morning and exchanged
views over Chinese economy and the financial crisis in Asia with
over 40 leading figures from the British business and financial
circles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
